{"title_page": "Norbert Bl\u00fcm", "text_new": "{{short description|German federal legislator}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Norbert Bl\u00fcm\n| image         = Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F078539-0037, Wiesbaden, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Bl\u00fcm.jpg \n| imagesize     = 250px\n| caption       = Norbert Bl\u00fcm in 1988\n| office        = Federal Minister for Social Affairs and Labour\n| term_start    = 4 October 1982 \n| term_end      = 27 October 1998\n| predecessor   = [[Heinz Westphal]]\n| successor     = [[Walter Riester]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1935|7|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], [[People's State of Hesse]], [[Nazi Germany]] \n| nationality   = [[Germany|German]] {{flagicon|Germany}}\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|2020|04|23|1935|7|21}}\n| death_place   = [[Bonn]], [[Germany]]\n| party         = [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|CDU]]\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Marita Bl\u00fcm|1964|2020|end=his death}}\n| children      = 3\n| residence     = [[Bonn]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Bonn]]\n| occupation    = \n| signature     = \n| website       = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F054629-0029, Ludwigshafen, CDU-Bundesparteitag.jpg|thumb|Norbert Bl\u00fcm (left) with [[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]] in 1978]]\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F073616-0021, Mainz, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Bl\u00fcm.jpg|thumb|Norbert Bl\u00fcm in 1986]]\n'''Norbert Bl\u00fcm''' (21 July 1935 \u2013 23 April 2020)<ref>{{cite news |last=L\u00fcke |first=Ulrich |date=24 April 2020 |title=Ein Gro\u00dfer der Bonner Republik |url=https://www.general-anzeiger-bonn.de/news/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-ist-tot-nachruf-auf-einen-grossen-der-bonner-republik_aid-50222203 |work=General Anzeiger |location=Bonn |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Zeit1\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm ist gestorben |url=https://www.zeit.de/politik/deutschland/2020-04/frueherer-arbeitsminister-norbert-bluem-gestorben |work=[[Die Zeit]] |location=Hamburg |agency=dpa |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Fr\u00fcherer Arbeitsminister Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/norbert-bluem-gestorben-1.4887153 |work=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] |location=Munich |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spiegel\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-frueherer-arbeitsminister-im-alter-von-84-jahren-gestorben-a-74ccbfb1-ce4f-4e06-b3d5-644ec7b31a23 |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> was a [[Germany|German]] politician, serving as [[Federation|federal]] [[legislator]] from [[North Rhine-Westphalia]], chairman of the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|CDU]] North Rhine-Westphalia (1987\u20131999), and [[Political minister|minister]] of labor and social affairs\u2014the only cabinet member who served in his function for all sixteen years of [[Helmut Kohl]]'s time as [[prime minister|Chancellor]] of Germany.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], Bl\u00fcm trained and worked locally as a toolmaker for [[Adam Opel AG|Opel]]. During this time, he was a founding member of the local Boy Scouts within the [[Deutsche Pfadfinderschaft Sankt Georg]]. In 1950, Bl\u00fcm joined the CDU.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hofmann |first=Gunter |date=24 April 2020 |title=K\u00e4mpfer f\u00fcr den Sozialstaat |url=https://www.zeit.de/politik/deutschland/2020-04/norbert-bluem-sozialpolitiker-cdu-helmut-kohl-minister-nachruf |work=[[Die Zeit]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> Later he studied German language and literature, history and philosophy. In 1967 he received his doctorate with the work ''Willenslehre und Soziallehre bei Ferdinand T\u00f6nnies. Ein Beitrag zum Verst\u00e4ndnis von \"Gemeinschaft und Gesellschaft\"'' (PhD).<ref name=\"Lingen\">{{cite web |last=Lingen |first=Markus |date=24 April 2020 |title=Geschichte der CDU: Norbert Bl\u00fcm |url=https://www.kas.de/de/web/geschichte-der-cdu/personen/biogramm-detail/-/content/norbert-bluem |work=kas.de |location=Berlin |publisher=Konrad-Adenauer-Stiftung e.V. |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1977 to 1987 Bl\u00fcm was chairman of the [[Christian Democratic Employees' Association]].<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /> He was member of the [[Bundestag]] (CDU, 1972\u20131981 and 1983\u20132002) and Deputy Federal Chairman of the CDU (1981\u20131990 and 1992\u20132000).<ref name=\"Lingen\" /> He was Federal Minister for Social Affairs and Labour from 1982 to 1998.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /> His most sustainable achievement was the introduction of care insurance in 1995.<ref name=\"Zeit1\" />\n\n==Political positions==\nDuring his time in office, Bl\u00fcm famously held out and pushed back against demands  by fellow Christian Democratic Union politicians, to raise the federal retirement age from 65 to 70.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mitchener |first=Brandon |date=9 November 1992 |title=German Public Spending Cuts Spark Infighting |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/11/09/business/worldbusiness/IHT-german-public-spending-cuts-spark-infighting.html |work=[[International Herald Tribune]] |location=New York City |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> His popular quote \"Die Rente ist sicher\" (loosely translated to: \"Pensions are untouchable\") is a misquotation. It was a slogan he wielded in 1986 (\"Eins ist sicher: Die Rente\", \"One thing is untouchable: pensions\"). This misquotation quickly gained notoriety in Germany and became a popular target for [[comedy]], as well as a cynical reference to be popularized by his opponents and critics for years to come. After almost three decades, Bl\u00fcm himself took part in it, by mocking said quote on the German TV show ''[[Neues aus der Anstalt]]''.\n\nBl\u00fcm was an outspoken critic of [[Scientology]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vehlewald |first1=Hans-J\u00f6rg |last2=Koelbl |first2=Susanne |date=27 November 1995 |title=\"Das ist Psychokrieg\" |url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-9236202.html |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> As a consequence, he was targeted by Scientology advocates, who would claim that the organization was a victim of religious [[discrimination]] in Germany.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=21 October 1996 |title=Anw\u00fcrfe aus \u00dcbersee |url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-9107899.html |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBl\u00fcm was paralyzed in arms and legs after blood poisoning in 2019.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /> He died on 23 April 2020 in Bonn.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/norbert-bluem-109.html |work=tagesschau.de |location=Hamburg |publisher=Norddeutscher Rundfunk |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n* Hans B\u00f6ckler Prize of the City of Cologne, Member of the Advisory Board<ref>[https://www.stadt-koeln.de/artikel/00045/index.html Hans B\u00f6ckler Prize, Kuratorium] City of Cologne.</ref>\n* Green Helmets, Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://gruenhelme.de/team-blank/kuratorium/ Board of Trustees] Green Helmets.</ref>\n* [[Bonn Minster]], Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://www.ksta.de/stiftung-fuer-das-bonner-muenster-13831158 Stiftung f\u00fcr das Bonner M\u00fcnster] [[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]], May 3, 2004.</ref>\n* St. Maria zur Wiese, Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://www.bauhuette-wiesenkirche.de/de/uber-uns/kuratorium/ Board of Trustees] St. Maria zur Wiese.</ref>\n* [[IG Metall]], Member (since 1949)\n\n==Recognition (selection)==\n* 2000 \u2013 [[M\u00fcnchhausen Prize]]\n* 2001 \u2013 [[Leipzig Human Rights Award]] \n* 2005 \u2013 [[Leopold Kunschak Prize]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{DNB portal|118722395}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009024102/http://www.partner-erde.de/deutsch/gruendung-rahmen.html |date=October 9, 2007 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm's article on the founding of the Scout Group \"Partner Erde\" in R\u00fcsselsheim ''(German)'' }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071115032636/http://xenutv.com/trust/leipzig-2001.htm The 2001 Leipzig Human Rights Award], video coverage of the event at ''[[Mark Bunker|Xenu TV]]'', June 9, 2001\n* [https://www.bundesarchiv.de/cocoon/barch/1121/z/z1960a/kap1_2/para2_124.html Kabinettsprotokolle Online \"Bl\u00fcm, Norbert\"]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blum, Norbert}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from R\u00fcsselsheim]]\n[[Category:Christian Democratic Union of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:People from the People's State of Hesse]]\n[[Category:Labor ministers (Germany)]]\n[[Category:Social Affairs ministers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n[[Category:Senators of Berlin]]\n[[Category:University of Bonn alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Leopold-Kunschak-Prize]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses with Star and Sash of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German federal legislator}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Norbert Bl\u00fcm\n| image         = Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F078539-0037, Wiesbaden, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Bl\u00fcm.jpg \n| imagesize     = 250px\n| caption       = Norbert Bl\u00fcm in 1988\n| office        = Federal Minister for Social Affairs and Labour\n| term_start    = 4 October 1982 \n| term_end      = 27 October 1998\n| predecessor   = [[Heinz Westphal]]\n| successor     = [[Walter Riester]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1935|7|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], [[People's State of Hesse]], [[Nazi Germany]] \n| nationality   = [[Germany|German]] {{flagicon|Germany}}\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|2020|04|23|1935|7|21}}\n| death_place   = [[Bonn]], [[Germany]]\n| party         = [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|CDU]]\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Marita Bl\u00fcm|1964|2020|end=his death}}\n| children      = 3\n| residence     = [[Bonn]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Bonn]]\n| occupation    = \n| signature     = \n| website       = \n| footnotes     = \n}}\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F054629-0029, Ludwigshafen, CDU-Bundesparteitag.jpg|thumb|Norbert Bl\u00fcm (left) with [[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]] in 1978]]\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F073616-0021, Mainz, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Bl\u00fcm.jpg|thumb|Norbert Bl\u00fcm in 1986]]\n'''Norbert Bl\u00fcm''' (21 July 1935 \u2013 23 April 2020)<ref>{{cite news |last=L\u00fcke |first=Ulrich |date=24 April 2020 |title=Ein Gro\u00dfer der Bonner Republik |url=https://www.general-anzeiger-bonn.de/news/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-ist-tot-nachruf-auf-einen-grossen-der-bonner-republik_aid-50222203 |work=General Anzeiger |location=Bonn |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Zeit1\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm ist gestorben |url=https://www.zeit.de/politik/deutschland/2020-04/frueherer-arbeitsminister-norbert-bluem-gestorben |work=[[Die Zeit]] |location=Hamburg |agency=dpa |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Fr\u00fcherer Arbeitsminister Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/norbert-bluem-gestorben-1.4887153 |work=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] |location=Munich |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spiegel\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-frueherer-arbeitsminister-im-alter-von-84-jahren-gestorben-a-74ccbfb1-ce4f-4e06-b3d5-644ec7b31a23 |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> was a [[Germany|German]] politician, serving as [[Federation|federal]] [[legislator]] from [[North Rhine-Westphalia]], chairman of the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|CDU]] North Rhine-Westphalia (1987\u20131999), and [[Political minister|minister]] of labor and social affairs\u2014the only cabinet member who served in his function for all sixteen years of [[Helmut Kohl]]'s time as [[prime minister|Chancellor]] of Germany.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], Bl\u00fcm trained locally as a toolmaker for [[Adam Opel AG|Opel]]. During this time, he was a founding member of the local Boy Scouts within the [[Deutsche Pfadfinderschaft Sankt Georg]]. In 1950, Bl\u00fcm joined the CDU.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hofmann |first=Gunter |date=24 April 2020 |title=K\u00e4mpfer f\u00fcr den Sozialstaat |url=https://www.zeit.de/politik/deutschland/2020-04/norbert-bluem-sozialpolitiker-cdu-helmut-kohl-minister-nachruf |work=[[Die Zeit]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> Later he studied German language and literature, history and philosophy. In 1967 he received his doctorate with the work ''Willenslehre und Soziallehre bei Ferdinand T\u00f6nnies. Ein Beitrag zum Verst\u00e4ndnis von \"Gemeinschaft und Gesellschaft\"'' (PhD).<ref name=\"Lingen\">{{cite web |last=Lingen |first=Markus |date=24 April 2020 |title=Geschichte der CDU: Norbert Bl\u00fcm |url=https://www.kas.de/de/web/geschichte-der-cdu/personen/biogramm-detail/-/content/norbert-bluem |work=kas.de |location=Berlin |publisher=Konrad-Adenauer-Stiftung e.V. |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1977 to 1987 Bl\u00fcm was chairman of the [[Christian Democratic Employees' Association]].<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /> He was member of the [[Bundestag]] (CDU, 1972\u20131981 and 1983\u20132002) and Deputy Federal Chairman of the CDU (1981\u20131990 and 1992\u20132000).<ref name=\"Lingen\" /> He was Federal Minister for Social Affairs and Labour from 1982 to 1998.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /> His most sustainable achievement was the introduction of care insurance in 1995.<ref name=\"Zeit1\" />\n\n==Political positions==\nDuring his time in office, Bl\u00fcm famously held out and pushed back against demands  by fellow Christian Democratic Union politicians, to raise the federal retirement age from 65 to 70.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mitchener |first=Brandon |date=9 November 1992 |title=German Public Spending Cuts Spark Infighting |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/11/09/business/worldbusiness/IHT-german-public-spending-cuts-spark-infighting.html |work=[[International Herald Tribune]] |location=New York City |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> His popular quote \"Die Rente ist sicher\" (loosely translated to: \"Pensions are untouchable\") is a misquotation. It was a slogan he wielded in 1986 (\"Eins ist sicher: Die Rente\", \"One thing is untouchable: pensions\"). This misquotation quickly gained notoriety in Germany and became a popular target for [[comedy]], as well as a cynical reference to be popularized by his opponents and critics for years to come. After almost three decades, Bl\u00fcm himself took part in it, by mocking said quote on the German TV show ''[[Neues aus der Anstalt]]''.\n\nBl\u00fcm was an outspoken critic of [[Scientology]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vehlewald |first1=Hans-J\u00f6rg |last2=Koelbl |first2=Susanne |date=27 November 1995 |title=\"Das ist Psychokrieg\" |url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-9236202.html |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> As a consequence, he was targeted by Scientology advocates, who would claim that the organization was a victim of religious [[discrimination]] in Germany.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=21 October 1996 |title=Anw\u00fcrfe aus \u00dcbersee |url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-9107899.html |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBl\u00fcm was paralyzed in arms and legs after blood poisoning in 2019.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /> He died on 23 April 2020 in Bonn.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/norbert-bluem-109.html |work=tagesschau.de |location=Hamburg |publisher=Norddeutscher Rundfunk |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n* Hans B\u00f6ckler Prize of the City of Cologne, Member of the Advisory Board<ref>[https://www.stadt-koeln.de/artikel/00045/index.html Hans B\u00f6ckler Prize, Kuratorium] City of Cologne.</ref>\n* Green Helmets, Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://gruenhelme.de/team-blank/kuratorium/ Board of Trustees] Green Helmets.</ref>\n* [[Bonn Minster]], Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://www.ksta.de/stiftung-fuer-das-bonner-muenster-13831158 Stiftung f\u00fcr das Bonner M\u00fcnster] [[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]], May 3, 2004.</ref>\n* St. Maria zur Wiese, Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://www.bauhuette-wiesenkirche.de/de/uber-uns/kuratorium/ Board of Trustees] St. Maria zur Wiese.</ref>\n* [[IG Metall]], Member (since 1949)\n\n==Recognition (selection)==\n* 2000 \u2013 [[M\u00fcnchhausen Prize]]\n* 2001 \u2013 [[Leipzig Human Rights Award]] \n* 2005 \u2013 [[Leopold Kunschak Prize]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{DNB portal|118722395}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009024102/http://www.partner-erde.de/deutsch/gruendung-rahmen.html |date=October 9, 2007 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm's article on the founding of the Scout Group \"Partner Erde\" in R\u00fcsselsheim ''(German)'' }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071115032636/http://xenutv.com/trust/leipzig-2001.htm The 2001 Leipzig Human Rights Award], video coverage of the event at ''[[Mark Bunker|Xenu TV]]'', June 9, 2001\n* [https://www.bundesarchiv.de/cocoon/barch/1121/z/z1960a/kap1_2/para2_124.html Kabinettsprotokolle Online \"Bl\u00fcm, Norbert\"]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blum, Norbert}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from R\u00fcsselsheim]]\n[[Category:Christian Democratic Union of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:People from the People's State of Hesse]]\n[[Category:Labor ministers (Germany)]]\n[[Category:Social Affairs ministers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n[[Category:Senators of Berlin]]\n[[Category:University of Bonn alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Leopold-Kunschak-Prize]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses with Star and Sash of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education:tweak", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norbert_Bl%C3%BCm"}
{"title_page": "St Ives, Cambridgeshire", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\n| official_name= St Ives\n<!-- IMAGE -->\n| static_image_name= Crown St, St Ives.JPG\n| static_image_caption= Crown Street\n<!-- MAP & LOCATION -->\n| os_grid_reference= TL305725\n| map_alt = St Ives shown within Cambridgeshire.\n| label_position = top\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.334362|-0.076147|display=inline,title}}\n| post_town= ST. IVES\n| postcode_district = PE27\n| postcode_area= PE\n| london_distance_km= 90\n| london_distance_mi=  \n| london_direction= South\n<!-- STATISTICS -->\n| population= 16,384\n| population_ref= <small>([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])</small>\n| area_total_sq_mi= \n| area_total_km2= 10.88\n| population_density= \n| area_footnotes= <ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=11128855&c=PE27+6SB&d=16&e=61&g=6406250&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=0&s=1403712447580&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2491/ |title=2011 Census area information |accessdate=25 June 2014 }}{{dead link|date=September 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n<!-- GOVERNANCE -->\n| shire_district= [[Huntingdonshire]]\n| shire_county = [[Cambridgeshire]]\n| region= East of England\n| constituency_westminster= [[Huntingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Huntingdon]]\n| dial_code= 01480\n }}\n\n'''St  Ives''' is a [[market town]] and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in  [[Cambridgeshire]], England,<ref name=OS153>{{cite map|title=Ordnance  Survey: Landranger map sheet 153 ''Bedford & Huntingdon (St Neots &  Biggleswade)''|ISBN= 9780319231722 |publisher=Ordnance  Survey|date=2013}}</ref> {{convert|5|mi|km|0}} east of [[Huntingdon]] and {{convert|12|mi|km|0}} north-west of [[Cambridge]]. Historically in [[Huntingdonshire]], St Ives is in the [[non-metropolitan district]] of the same name which covers a similar area to the [[historic counties of England|historic county]].\n\n==History==\nPreviously called '''Slepe''', its name was changed to St Ives after the body of [[Ivo of Huntingdonshire|Saint Ivo]] (claimed to have been a [[Persian people|Persian]] [[bishop]]; not to be confused with [[Ivo of Kermartin]]) was found buried in the town in about 1001/2. St Ivo's Priory was built on the site where the body was discovered.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nSt Ives was listed as Slepe in the [[hundred (county division)|Hundred]] of [[Hurstingstone (hundred)|Hurstingstone]] in Huntingdonshire  in the [[Domesday Book]].<ref name=\"PenIndex\">{{cite book|title=Domesday Book: A Complete Translation |publisher=Penguin Books |date=1992 |location =London|editors= Dr Ann Williams, Professor G.H. Martin|page=1402|isbn=0-141-00523-8}}</ref> In 1086 there was one manor and 64 households, 29. 5{{clarify|date=October 2019}} [[Carucate|ploughlands]], {{convert|60|acre|hectare|0}} of meadows and {{convert|1892|acre|hectare|0}} of woodland.<ref name=\"OD86\">{{cite web|url=http://opendomesday.org/place/TL3171/st-ives|title=Open Domesday: Place - St Ives|author=Professor J.J.N. Palmer, University of Hull|website=www. opendomesday.org|publisher=Anna Powell-Smith|accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor the past 1,000 years St Ives has been home to some of the biggest markets in the country, and in the 13th century it was an important [[entrep\u00f4t]]. Today it remains an important market in [[East Anglia]].\n\nBuilt on the banks of the wide [[River Great Ouse]] between [[Huntingdon]] and [[Ely, Cambridgeshire|Ely]], St Ives has a famous [[St Ives Bridge|chapel on its bridge]]. In the [[Anglo-Saxon]] era, St Ives's position on the Great Ouse was strategic, as it controlled the last natural crossing point or ford on the river, {{convert|80|km|mi}} from the sea. The flint reef in the bed of the river at this point gave rise to a ford, which then provided the foundations for the celebrated bridge.\n\nDuring the 18th and 19th centuries, St Ives was a hub of trade and navigation, and the town had dozens of inns and many bawdy houses {{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}. Goods were brought into the town on barges, and livestock rested on the last fattening grounds before delivery to London's [[Smithfield Market]]. As the railway network expanded and roads improved, the use of the River Great Ouse declined. It is now mostly used for leisure boats and recreation.\n\nThe river Great Ouse at St Ives flooded in 1947, and some parts suffered seriously again at Easter 1998<ref>{{cite web|url=http://saint-ives.info/history/Floods/ |title=1998 Floods in St Ives |accessdate=6 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721232441/http://saint-ives.info/history/Floods/ |archivedate=21 July 2011 }}</ref> and in January 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.st-ives.info/history/floods2003/ |title=2003 Floods in St Ives|accessdate=6 September 2009}}</ref> Extensive flood protection works were carried out on both sides of the river in 2006-07 at a cost of nearly \u00a39&nbsp;million. {{convert|500|m|ft}} of brick-clad steel-piling was put into place to protect the town, most noticeably at the Waits, where a plaza has also been created. A further {{convert|750|m|ft}} on the other side of the river protects [[Hemingford Grey]], reducing the yearly risk of flooding from 10% to 1%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/6231974.stm|title=\u00a38. 8m flood defence scheme opened|date=22 June 2007|work=BBC News|accessdate=6 September 2009}}</ref> Building on the flood plain at St Ives is now discouraged.\n\nOriginal historical documents relating to St Ives, including the original [[parish church]] registers, local government records, maps and photographs, are held by [[Cambridgeshire Archives and Local Studies]] at the County Record Office in [[Huntingdon]].\n\n==Governance==\nAs a civil parish, St Ives has a [[Parish councils in England|town council]] consisting of seventeen councillors including a [[Mayors in England|Town Mayor]] and a deputy Town Mayor.<ref>{{cite web|title=St Ives Town Council: Councillors|url=http://www.stivestowncouncil.gov.uk/index.php/council/councillors|website=www.stivestowncouncil.gov.uk|publisher=St Ives Town Council|accessdate=8 February 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311125847/http://www.stivestowncouncil.gov.uk/index.php/council/councillors|archivedate=11 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The second tier of local government is [[Huntingdonshire District Council]], a [[non-metropolitan district]] of Cambridgeshire. St Ives has three district wards for the district counci; ''St Ives East'', ''St Ives South'', and ''St Ives West''.<ref name=\"OSelec\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/election-maps/gb/# |title=Ordnance Survey Election Maps |website=www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk |publisher=Ordnance Survey |accessdate=4 February 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220103943/https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/election-maps/gb/ |archivedate=20 February 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''St Ives East'' and ''St Ives South'' are both represented by two district councillors, and ''St Ives West'' is represented on the district council by one councillor.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.huntsdc.gov.uk/council-democracy/meetings-and-decision-making/councillors/ |title=Huntingdonshire District Council: Councillors |website=www.huntsdc.gov.uk |publisher=Huntingdonshire District Council |accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref> For St Ives the highest tier of local government is [[Cambridgeshire County Council]]. St Ives is part of the electoral division of ''St Ives'' <ref name=\"OSelec\" /> and is represented on the county council by two councillors.<ref name=\"CCC1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/info/20087/councillors_and_meetings/313/county_councillors|title=Cambridgeshire County Council: Councillors|website=www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk|publisher=Cambridgeshire County Council|accessdate=15 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160222112615/http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/info/20087/councillors_and_meetings/313/county_councillors|archive-date=22 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSt Ives was in the historic and [[administrative county]] of Huntingdonshire until 1965. From 1965, the village was part of the new administrative county of [[Huntingdon and Peterborough]]. In 1974, following the [[Local Government Act 1972]], St Ives became a part of the county of Cambridgeshire.\n\nAt Westminster St Ives is in the parliamentary constituency of [[Huntingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Huntingdon]],<ref name=\"OSelec\" /> and since 2001 has been represented in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] by [[Jonathan Djanogly]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]).\n\n==Geography==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2008}}\nSt Ives was the subject of town planning at a very early date,{{When|date=February 2009}} giving it a spacious town centre. Portions of the open space between Merryland and Crown Street were lost to market stalls that turned into permanent buildings. Some of the shops in the town centre are still in the same layout as in [[medieval]] times, one [[rod (length)|rod]] in width, the standard length for floor and roof [[joist]]s. The lanes along the north side of town are believed to follow the layout of the narrow medieval fields, and are slightly S-shaped because of the way ploughs turned at each end. Similar field boundaries can be seen in Warners Park.\n\n==Demography==\n===Population===\nIn the period 1801 to 1901 the population of St Ives was recorded every ten years by the [[Census in the United Kingdom|UK census]].  During this time the population was in the range of 2,099 (the lowest was in 1801) and 3,572 (the highest was in 1851).<ref name=Camin>{{cite web |title=Historic Census figures Cambridgeshire to 2011 |publisher=Cambridgeshire Insight |website=www.cambridgeshireinsight.org.uk |accessdate=12 February 2016 |url=http://www.cambridgeshireinsight.org.uk/file/2001/download |format=xlsx - download |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215102922/http://www.cambridgeshireinsight.org.uk/file/2001/download |archivedate=15 February 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1901, a census was taken every ten years with the exception of 1941 (due to the [[Second World War]]).\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size: 9pt\"\n|-\n!width=\"150\"|Parish<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1911<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1921<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1931<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1951<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1961<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1971<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1981<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1991<br>\n!width=\"30\"|2001<br>\n!width=\"30\"|2011 <br>\n|-\n|align=left|St Ives\n|align=\"center\"|3,015\n|align=\"center\"|2,797\n|align=\"center\"|2,664\n|align=\"center\"|3,078\n|align=\"center\"|4,082\n|align=\"center\"|7,148\n|align=\"center\"|12,331\n|align=\"center\"|14,930\n|align=\"center\"|16,001\n|align=\"center\"|16,384\n|-\n|}\n\n<small>\nAll population census figures from report ''Historic Census figures Cambridgeshire to 2011'' by ''Cambridgeshire Insight''.<ref name=Camin/>\n</small>\n\nIn 2011, the parish covered an area of {{convert|2688|acre|hectare|0}}<ref name=Camin/> and the population density of St Ives in 2011 was 3901 persons per square mile (1505.9 per square kilometre).\n\n==Economy==\nThe Monday market takes over the town centre, and is larger in scale on [[Bank Holiday]]s in May and August. There is a Friday market, and a [[Farmers' Market]] on the first and third Saturday every month. The [[Michaelmas]] Fair takes over for three days from the second Monday in October, and there is a carnival<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.stives-town.info/carnival/2006/2006_st_ives_carnival_parade.htm |title = The 2006 St Ives Carnival Parade}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.st-ives.info/fun/Carnival/ | title=St-ives.info}}</ref> which is the biggest public gathering in [[Huntingdonshire]]. The town has a mixture of shops, bars, coffee lounges, a department store and other amenities.\n\n==Public houses{{anchor|Golden Lion, St Ives}}==\n[[File:Market stalls in front of the Golden Lion Hotel, St Ives - geograph.org.uk - 310810.jpg|thumb|right|The Golden Lion, a former coaching inn]]\n\nAs an important market town, St Ives always needed large numbers of public houses, many of which were [[brothel|bawdy houses]]: 64 in 1838 (1 for every 55 inhabitants), 60 in 1861, 48 in 1865 and 45 in 1899, although only five of these made the owners a living. As livestock sales diminished, however, so did the need for large numbers of pubs, falling to a low point of 16 in 1962. In that year the ''Seven Wives'' on Ramsey Road was opened and, with some openings and closings since, there are 17 today. The oldest name is the ''Dolphin''; in use on the same site for over 300 years, it's current usage is for a hotel built in 1985. Next oldest is the ''White Hart'', which is pre-1720. ''Nelson's Head'' and ''Golden Lion'' are at least as old but have not kept the same name: they used to be called the ''Three Tuns'' and the ''Red Lion'' respectively. There has been a pub on the site of the ''Robin Hood'' from a similar date; in fact it was originally two separate pubs: the ''Angel'' and the ''Swan''. The claim of the Royal Oak to date from 1502 cannot be proven since, while a portion at the back is 17th-century (making it physically the oldest portion of any pub in St Ives), the pub name is more recent. The reference is to [[Charles II of England|Charles II]]'s famous escape from [[Oliver Cromwell|Cromwell]]'s [[Roundheads]], and Charles was restored to the throne in 1660.<ref>{{citation|title=The Pubs of St Ives|first=Bob|last=Burn-Murdoch|edition=3rd|publisher=Friends of the Norris Museum|date=16 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Golden Lion'' was a 19th-century [[coaching inn]].<ref name=fisher>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YWyrAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA151&dq=%22Golden+Lion%22 |title=British River Navigations: Inland Cuts, Fens, Dikes, Channels and Non-tidal Rivers |publisher=A&C Black |author=Stuart Fisher |year=2013 |page=151 |accessdate=29 July 2014|isbn=9781472906687 }}</ref> ''The Official Guide to the Great Eastern Railway'' referred to it in 1893 as one of two \"leading hotels\" in St Ives<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6MJRAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA271 |title=The Official Guide to the Great Eastern Railway |publisher=Cassell |author=Great Eastern Railway |year=1893 |page=271 |accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref> and there are a number of ghost stories associated with the pub.<ref name=fisher/><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EH-IAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT53&dq=%22Golden+Lion%22 |title=Paranormal Cambridgeshire |publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited |author=Damien O'Dell |year=2013 |page=53 |accessdate=29 July 2014|isbn=9781445629940 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KkqIAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT69&dq=%22Golden+Lion%22 |title=Military Ghosts |publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited |author=Alan Wood |year=2013 |page=69 |accessdate=29 July 2014|isbn=9781445625225 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a-nWAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Golden+Lion%22++%22St+Ives%22 |title=The International Directory of Haunted Places |publisher=Penguin Group |author=Dennis William Hauck |year=2000 |page=18 |accessdate=29 July 2014|isbn=9780140296358 }}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:St Ives, Cambridgeshire, England-7Aug2011.jpg|thumb|St Ives bridge and the River Great Ouse]]\n[[File:St Ives Cambs Oliver Cromwell statue.jpg|upright|thumb|The [[Statue of Oliver Cromwell, St Ives|Statue of Oliver Cromwell]] on Market Hill in the town centre]]\n\n===St Ives Bridge===\n{{Main|St Ives Bridge}}\nSt Ives Bridge is most unusual in incorporating a [[chapel]], the most striking of only four examples in England. Also unusual are its two southern arches which are a different shape from the rest of the bridge, being rounded instead of slightly [[gothic architecture|gothic]]. After the dissolution of the monasteries in 1537, the chapel was given to the prior to live in. The lords of the manor of St Ives changed hands several times, as did the chapel. During this period, it was in turn - a private house, a doctors surgery and a pub, called Little Hell. The pub had a reputation for rowdy behaviour, and it is believed the landlord kept pigs in the basement. The additional two storeys added in the seventeenth century were removed in 1930, due to damage being caused to the foundations. \nThe chapel features colourfully in the historical novel 'Not Just a Whore', by local St Ives resident K M Warwick, where it is described as a fictitious \"Bawdy House\" (brothel). The bridge was partially rebuilt after [[Oliver Cromwell]] knocked down two arches during the [[English Civil War]] to prevent [[Charles I of England|King Charles I's]] troops approaching London from the [[Cavalier|Royalist]] base in [[Lincolnshire]]. During the war and for some period afterwards, the gap was covered by a [[drawbridge]]. The town square contains a [[Statue of Oliver Cromwell, St Ives|statue of Oliver Cromwell]] erected in 1901. It is one of four statues of Cromwell on public display in Britain, the others being in [[Parliament Square]], outside [[Wythenshawe Hall]] and in [[Warrington]].\n\nSt Ives Corn Exchange is the home of St Ives Youth Theatre (SIYT).\n\n===Holt Island===\nThe eastern or town end of Holt Island is nature reserve, and the western end, opposite the parish church, is a facility for the Sea [[Scouts]]. The scout portion contains what was, before the opening of the Leisure Centre, the town's outdoor town swimming pool. The pool was dug in 1913 and closed to the public in 1949.<ref name=StIvesMillenium>{{cite news|title=St Ives a new Millenium|pages=8&ndash;9|newspaper=St Ives Photo Publication Group|publisher=Inchcape|year= 2002}}{{sic}}</ref> It is now used by the scouts for canoeing and rappelling. In November 1995, the island was the locus of a significant lawsuit and a break-away Scouting Association was prevented from using and developing a claim to it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lgcplus.com/news/scouts-fight-for-right-to-island/1563962.article|title=SCOUTS FIGHT FOR RIGHT TO ISLAND|work=[[Local Government Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Emap Communications]]|date=19 November 1995|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Culture and community==\nThe Norris Museum holds a great deal of local history, including a number of books written by its former curator, Bob Burn-Murdoch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norrismuseum.org.uk/ |title=Norris Museum |publisher=Norris Museum. |date= |accessdate=2012-06-11}}</ref>  After over 30 years of service, Bob Burn-Murdoch retired in December 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Ives museum comes to an end of an era|url=http://www.huntspost.co.uk/news/latest-news/st_ives_museum_comes_to_end_of_an_era_as_curator_announces_retirement_1_1475853|accessdate=17 March 2013|newspaper=Hunts Post|date=9 August 2012}}</ref> \nThe Norris Museum was founded by Herbert Norris, who left his lifetime's collection of Huntingdonshire relics to the people of St Ives when he died in 1931.It has recently been reopened in August 2017, following a \u00a31.5m refurbishment and expansion made possible by a Heritage Lottery Fund grant. Its current director is Sarah Russell, and it is managed by the Norris Management Trust, made up of members of St Ives Town Council and the Friends of the Norris Museum.\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:St ives rowing club.jpg|thumb|Boathouse of St Ives Rowing Club]]\nThere are 2 leisure facilities, the indoor centre is adjacent to the Burgess conference and Events Hall and an outdoor centre in the west of the town. The original swimming pool, fed by the river, is in the middle of Holt Island and is now used for canoeing practice and other activities. St Ives also has a [[Rugby union|Rugby]] club on Somersham Road,<ref>{{cite web|last=Kirby |first=Andy |url=http://www.stivesrufc.co.uk |title=St Ives Rugby Union Football Club |publisher=Stivesrufc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-06-11}}</ref> and a [[Non-League football]] club, [[St Ives Town F.C.]], which plays at Westwood Road.  The St Ives Rowing Club was once captained by [[John Goldie (barrister)|John Goldie]] and has had a number of members who have competed at Olympic and Commonwealth championships.\n\nThere is an active swimming club. New members are always welcome, from age 4\u00bd upwards, whatever their swimming ability and can be slotted into (and trained up to) teaching groups, a pre-competitive group, development squads or senior/competitive squads [http://www.stivesswimclub.co.uk]\n\nSt Ives has an 18 hole championship golf course, located 1/2 mile east of St Ives on the A1123. It opened in the summer of 2010, replacing the previous 9 hole course on Westwood Road/ High Leys. \n[http://www.stivesgolfclub.co.uk/]\n\nEach year the town hosts a free 2 day carnival and music festival which was launched in 1999, as part of the committee set up for the millennium. This is now part of the towns tradition and it grows year on year.\n\n==Education==\nSt Ives has a main [[secondary school]], [[St Ivo School]]. Eastfield nursery and infant school, Westfield Junior school and two [[primary school]]s Thorndown and Wheatfields.\nIn 2018, a plan was announced to combine and expand Eastfield and Westfield in to one larger community primary school.\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Guided busway===\n{{Main|Cambridgeshire Guided Busway}}\nThe major section of the world's longest guided busway, using all new construction techniques and technology, connects St Ives directly to [[Cambridge Science Park]] on the outskirts of [[Cambridge]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/db/pressrel.nsf/cac74a2aba838b5d80256b56004e53ab/edcbd21f6a9cf5b880257295004c237b?OpenDocument|title=Secretary Of State Celebrates Start Of Works On Guided Busway|publisher=[[Cambridgeshire County Council]]|date=5 March 2007|accessdate=6 September 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090606040816/http://www2.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/db/pressrel.nsf/cac74a2aba838b5d80256b56004e53ab/edcbd21f6a9cf5b880257295004c237b?OpenDocument|archivedate=6 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> along the route of a disused railway line. The same buses continue into the centre of Cambridge along regular roads in one direction and continue to [[Huntingdon]] in the other direction. A shorter section of the same busway system operates from the [[Cambridge railway station|railway station]] on the far side of Cambridge to [[Addenbrooke's Hospital]] and [[Trumpington, Cambridgeshire|Trumpington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/transport/guided/|title=The Busway Network|publisher=[[Cambridgeshire County Council]]|accessdate=6 September 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416144840/http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/transport/guided/|archivedate=16 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The scheme, budgeted at \u00a3116.2 million, opened in summer 2011. Construction of the busway was beset with problems, causing delays; for example, cracks appeared in the structure allowing weeds to grow through. Contractors BAM Nuttall were fined a significant amount of money for each day that the busway completion date was not met.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/40F67C0E-CB57-4327-A7BE-440650E8B822/0/CGBleafletweb.pdf|title=Cambridgeshire Guided Busway - Information about the scheme|publisher=[[Cambridgeshire County Council]]|date=10 January 2007|accessdate=6 September 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528012536/http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/40F67C0E-CB57-4327-A7BE-440650E8B822/0/CGBleafletweb.pdf|archivedate=28 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe St Ives [[Park & Ride]] on Meadow Lane is part of the scheme and will open at the same time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/346A6FC8-8095-471B-88CB-41DCAB168459/0/GBnewsletterOct08hires.pdf |title=Guided Busway Update |date=October 2008 |publisher=[[Cambridgeshire County Council]] |accessdate=6 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609185118/http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/346A6FC8-8095-471B-88CB-41DCAB168459/0/GBnewsletterOct08hires.pdf |archivedate=9 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> A \"Green Update\" newsletter came out in Winter 2007 with news on conservation work including protection of the Great Crested Newt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3D59D72B-2A13-49A7-869E-62DB5CDC0629/0/CGBGreenUpdate.pdf |title=Guided Busway Green Update - Winter 2007 |date=26 November 2007 |accessdate=6 September 2009 |publisher=[[cambridgeshire County Council]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609185202/http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3D59D72B-2A13-49A7-869E-62DB5CDC0629/0/CGBGreenUpdate.pdf |archivedate=9 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Road===\nSt Ives is just off the [[A14 road (England)|A14]] road on a particularly congested section of the route from the [[UK]]'s second city, [[Birmingham]], to the port of [[Felixstowe]] and thence to the mainland of [[Europe]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teletrac.net/__assets/ksrwvo1ouk6smobtjr.pdf|title=Trafficmaster/RAC Foundation Congestion report: Volume 2|page=9|publisher=Trafficmaster plc and RAC Foundation for Motoring|accessdate=6 September 2009}}{{Dead link|date=September 2009}}</ref> This {{convert|32|km|adj=on}} section of road also links the northern end of the M11 ([[Cambridge]] and region) to the [[M1 motorway (England)|M1]] and the whole of the [[North of England]] and [[Scotland]]. A new by-pass is planned for St Ives and [[Huntingdon]], leaving the existing alignment near [[Swavesey]] and passing to the south of both market towns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/documents/A14_Ellington_to_Fen_Ditton_Public_Exhibition_Leaflet.pdf |title=Ellington to Fen Ditton Improvemebt |date=November 2008 |accessdate=6 September 2009 |publisher=[[Highways Agency]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605141735/http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/documents/A14_Ellington_to_Fen_Ditton_Public_Exhibition_Leaflet.pdf |archivedate=5 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> A northern bypass has been under discussion for even longer but is not anticipated any time soon.\n\n===Rail and conventional bus===\nBus services are provided by Stagecoach in Huntingdonshire and Go Whippet, the former also having its depot near the town. Services to [[Cambridge]] and [[Huntingdon]] are frequent during the day, though less frequent in the evenings.  There are also buses to Somersham, Ramsey and Cambourne.\n\nBetween 1847 and 1970 the town was served by [[St Ives (Cambridgeshire) railway station|St Ives railway station]] on the [[Cambridge and Huntingdon railway]].<ref name=subbrit>{{cite web|url=http://www.subbrit.org.uk/sb-sites/stations/s/st.ives/index.shtml|title=Station Name:ST. IVES (Huntingdonshire)|publisher=www.subbrit.org.uk|accessdate=29 October 2008|first=Nick|last=Catford}}</ref> The line from Cambridge and the station almost survived the 1963 to 1973 [[Beeching Axe]], but were lost to passenger service in the final stages of the process. Some sections continued to be used for freight until 1993. A campaign to reopen the passenger rail service only ended with the ripping-up of disused track shortly before construction of the Guided Busway. Huntingdon, {{convert|7|mile|km}}) away, has the nearest railway station. Buses using the Busway system provide direct links to both Huntingdon and Cambridge stations.\n\n==Religious sites==\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2016}}\n[[File:cmglee_St_Ives_All_Saints_Parish_Church.jpg|thumb|upright|All Saints parish church, May 2014.]]\n[[File:cmglee St Ives Market Hill.jpg|thumb|upright|The Free Church and Market Hill.]]\nThere are ten places of worship, including the ancient [[parish church]]. Many other Christian denominations are also represented, and the town also has a [[mosque]] and an [[Islamic]] Community Centre.\n\nAll Saints Church ([[Church of England]]) on Church Street has been in the town since AD970 and is one of only two [[Grade I listed building]]s in the town, the other being The Bridge. Originally the parish church of the settlement of Slepe, before St Ives came into existence, it now enjoys a tranquil location at the end of Church Street, situated to the west of the town centre. All Saints, as it stands today, dates largely from the rebuilding of the late 15th century. It was extensively reordered in the late 19th century by [[Ninian Comper|Sir Ninian Comper]].\n\nThe church which dominates the town's market place, is The Free Church ([[United Reformed Church]]). This was built in 1864, but was modernised in 1980, moving the worship area upstairs. The [[Sacred Heart Church, St Ives|Church of the Sacred Heart]] ([[Roman Catholic]]) on Needingworth Road, was originally built by [[Augustus Pugin]] in Cambridge, but was dismantled in 1902 and transported by barge to St Ives. The hall at the back was added in about 2001. The current [[Methodist Church]] on The Waits opened in 1905. Crossways Church ([[Assembly of God]]) meet at Crossways Christian Centre on Ramsey Road. St Ives Christian Fellowship (Partnership) meet at Thorndown Junior School on Hill Rise. The Bridge Church (New Frontiers) meet in a newly renovated former industrial building on the corner of Burrel Road and Marley Road. St Ives Evangelical Christian Church ([[Evangelicalism|Evangelical]]) meet at the Burleigh Hill Community Centre, off Constable Road.\n\n==Cultural references==\n[[File:St Ives Seven Wives PH At Night.jpg|thumb|The Seven Wives pub on a summer's night]] \nThe town name is featured in the anonymous nursery rhyme/riddle \"[[As I was going to St Ives]]\". While sometimes claimed to be [[St Ives, Cornwall]], the man with seven wives, each with seven sacks containing seven cats etc. may have been on his way to (or coming from) the [[fair|Great Fair]] at St Ives.<ref>{{citation |title=St Ives, Slepe by the Ouse |first=Noel |last=Hudson |year=1989 |page=131 |publisher=St Ives Town Council |isbn=978-0-9515298-0-5}}</ref> On Ramsey Road there is a [[public house]] called The Seven Wives, though this is a modern pub with no connection to the ancient rhyme other than the name.<ref>Indeed in the earliest recorded English version of the riddle, of 1730, there were nine wives. See main article.</ref>\n\nThe term '''tawdry''' is a St Ives derived word (vying with the rival Ely claim), basically meaning something that is 'cheap and cheerful', and was evolved directly from the St Audrey's Lane cloth market held during the mediaeval and later ages.  Made from discarded inferior wool and/or other felt fibres, it was a popular source of cheap material bought by the locals, and those further afield, who flocked to the market in their droves to buy cheap supplies for their own domestic clothing.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe famous war poet [[Rupert Brooke]] lived at [[Grantchester]] some {{convert|32|km|mi}} away in the same [[county]]. In his famous poem \"''[[The Old Vicarage, Grantchester]]''\" he heaped praise on his own village, but not on the [[shire town]] of [[Cambridge]] itself, or on the other villages around. Of St Ives he wrote:\n{{cquote|Strong men have blanched and shot their wives, rather than send them to St Ives<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.orchard-grantchester.com/poetry.html|title=The Old Vicarage, Grantchester|first=Rupert|last=Brooke|place=Caf\u00e9 des Westerns, Berlin|date=May 1912|accessdate=21 March 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302153404/http://www.orchard-grantchester.com/poetry.html|archivedate=2 March 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n''St Ives, Slepe by the Ouse'', by Noel Hudson. Black Bear Press, 1989, {{ISBN|0-9515298-0-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n* [http://www.stivestowncouncil.gov.uk/ St Ives Town Council web-site]\n\n{{River Great Ouse|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Ives, Cambridgeshire}}\n[[Category:St Ives, Cambridgeshire| ]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Huntingdonshire]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the River Great Ouse]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Towns in Cambridgeshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\n| official_name= St Ives\n<!-- IMAGE -->\n| static_image_name= Crown St, St Ives.JPG\n| static_image_caption= Crown Street\n<!-- MAP & LOCATION -->\n| os_grid_reference= TL305725\n| map_alt = St Ives shown within Cambridgeshire.\n| label_position = top\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.334362|-0.076147|display=inline,title}}\n| post_town= ST. IVES\n| postcode_district = PE27\n| postcode_area= PE\n| london_distance_km= 90\n| london_distance_mi=  \n| london_direction= South\n<!-- STATISTICS -->\n| population= 16,384\n| population_ref= <small>([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]])</small>\n| area_total_sq_mi= \n| area_total_km2= 10.88\n| population_density= \n| area_footnotes= <ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=11128855&c=PE27+6SB&d=16&e=61&g=6406250&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=0&s=1403712447580&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2491/ |title=2011 Census area information |accessdate=25 June 2014 }}{{dead link|date=September 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n<!-- GOVERNANCE -->\n| shire_district= [[Huntingdonshire]]\n| shire_county = [[Cambridgeshire]]\n| region= East of England\n| constituency_westminster= [[Huntingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Huntingdon]]\n| dial_code= 01480\n }}\n\n'''St  Ives''' is a [[market town]] and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in  [[Cambridgeshire]], England,<ref name=OS153>{{cite map|title=Ordnance  Survey: Landranger map sheet 153 ''Bedford & Huntingdon (St Neots &  Biggleswade)''|ISBN= 9780319231722 |publisher=Ordnance  Survey|date=2013}}</ref> {{convert|5|mi|km|0}} east of [[Huntingdon]] and {{convert|12|mi|km|0}} north-west of [[Cambridge]]. Historically in [[Huntingdonshire]], St Ives is in the [[non-metropolitan district]] of the same name which covers a similar area to the [[historic counties of England|historic county]].\n\n==History==\nPreviously called '''Slepe''', its name was changed to St Ives after the body of [[Ivo of Huntingdonshire|Saint Ivo]] (claimed to have been a [[Persian people|Persian]] [[bishop]]; not to be confused with [[Ivo of Kermartin]]) was found buried in the town in about 1001/2. St Ivo's Priory was built on the site where the body was discovered.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nSt Ives was listed as Slepe in the [[hundred (county division)|Hundred]] of [[Hurstingstone (hundred)|Hurstingstone]] in Huntingdonshire  in the [[Domesday Book]].<ref name=\"PenIndex\">{{cite book|title=Domesday Book: A Complete Translation |publisher=Penguin Books |date=1992 |location =London|editors= Dr Ann Williams, Professor G.H. Martin|page=1402|isbn=0-141-00523-8}}</ref> In 1086 there was one manor and 64 households, 29. 5{{clarify|date=October 2019}} [[Carucate|ploughlands]], {{convert|60|acre|hectare|0}} of meadows and {{convert|1892|acre|hectare|0}} of woodland.<ref name=\"OD86\">{{cite web|url=http://opendomesday.org/place/TL3171/st-ives|title=Open Domesday: Place - St Ives|author=Professor J.J.N. Palmer, University of Hull|website=www. opendomesday.org|publisher=Anna Powell-Smith|accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor the past 1,000 years St Ives has been home to some of the biggest markets in the country, and in the 13th century it was an important [[entrep\u00f4t]]. Today it remains an important market in [[East Anglia]].\n\nBuilt on the banks of the wide [[River Great Ouse]] between [[Huntingdon]] and [[Ely, Cambridgeshire|Ely]], St Ives has a famous [[St Ives Bridge|chapel on its bridge]]. In the [[Anglo-Saxon]] era, St Ives's position on the Great Ouse was strategic, as it controlled the last natural crossing point or ford on the river, {{convert|80|km|mi}} from the sea. The flint reef in the bed of the river at this point gave rise to a ford, which then provided the foundations for the celebrated bridge.\n\nDuring the 18th and 19th centuries, St Ives was a hub of trade and navigation, and the town had dozens of inns and many bawdy houses {{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}. Goods were brought into the town on barges, and livestock rested on the last fattening grounds before delivery to London's [[Smithfield Market]]. As the railway network expanded and roads improved, the use of the River Great Ouse declined. It is now mostly used for leisure boats and recreation.\n\nThe river Great Ouse at St Ives flooded in 1947, and some parts suffered seriously again at Easter 1998<ref>{{cite web|url=http://saint-ives.info/history/Floods/ |title=1998 Floods in St Ives |accessdate=6 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721232441/http://saint-ives.info/history/Floods/ |archivedate=21 July 2011 }}</ref> and in January 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.st-ives.info/history/floods2003/ |title=2003 Floods in St Ives|accessdate=6 September 2009}}</ref> Extensive flood protection works were carried out on both sides of the river in 2006-07 at a cost of nearly \u00a39&nbsp;million. {{convert|500|m|ft}} of brick-clad steel-piling was put into place to protect the town, most noticeably at the Waits, where a plaza has also been created. A further {{convert|750|m|ft}} on the other side of the river protects [[Hemingford Grey]], reducing the yearly risk of flooding from 10% to 1%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/6231974.stm|title=\u00a38. 8m flood defence scheme opened|date=22 June 2007|work=BBC News|accessdate=6 September 2009}}</ref> Building on the flood plain at St Ives is now discouraged.\n\nOriginal historical documents relating to St Ives, including the original [[parish church]] registers, local government records, maps and photographs, are held by [[Cambridgeshire Archives and Local Studies]] at the County Record Office in [[Huntingdon]].\n\n==Governance==\nAs a civil parish, St Ives has a [[Parish councils in England|town council]] consisting of seventeen councillors including a major and a deputy-mayor.<ref>{{cite web|title=St Ives Town Council: Councillors|url=http://www.stivestowncouncil.gov.uk/index.php/council/councillors|website=www.stivestowncouncil.gov.uk|publisher=St Ives Town Council|accessdate=8 February 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311125847/http://www.stivestowncouncil.gov.uk/index.php/council/councillors|archivedate=11 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The second tier of local government is [[Huntingdonshire District Council]], a [[non-metropolitan district]] of Cambridgeshire. St Ives has three district wards for the district counci; ''St Ives East'', ''St Ives South'', and ''St Ives West''.<ref name=\"OSelec\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/election-maps/gb/# |title=Ordnance Survey Election Maps |website=www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk |publisher=Ordnance Survey |accessdate=4 February 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220103943/https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/election-maps/gb/ |archivedate=20 February 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''St Ives East'' and ''St Ives South'' are both represented by two district councillors, and ''St Ives West'' is represented on the district council by one councillor.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.huntsdc.gov.uk/council-democracy/meetings-and-decision-making/councillors/ |title=Huntingdonshire District Council: Councillors |website=www.huntsdc.gov.uk |publisher=Huntingdonshire District Council |accessdate=4 February 2016}}</ref> For St Ives the highest tier of local government is [[Cambridgeshire County Council]]. St Ives is part of the electoral division of ''St Ives'' <ref name=\"OSelec\" /> and is represented on the county council by two councillors.<ref name=\"CCC1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/info/20087/councillors_and_meetings/313/county_councillors|title=Cambridgeshire County Council: Councillors|website=www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk|publisher=Cambridgeshire County Council|accessdate=15 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160222112615/http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/info/20087/councillors_and_meetings/313/county_councillors|archive-date=22 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSt Ives was in the historic and [[administrative county]] of Huntingdonshire until 1965. From 1965, the village was part of the new administrative county of [[Huntingdon and Peterborough]]. In 1974, following the [[Local Government Act 1972]], St Ives became a part of the county of Cambridgeshire.\n\nAt Westminster St Ives is in the parliamentary constituency of [[Huntingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Huntingdon]],<ref name=\"OSelec\" /> and since 2001 has been represented in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] by [[Jonathan Djanogly]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]).\n\n==Geography==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2008}}\nSt Ives was the subject of town planning at a very early date,{{When|date=February 2009}} giving it a spacious town centre. Portions of the open space between Merryland and Crown Street were lost to market stalls that turned into permanent buildings. Some of the shops in the town centre are still in the same layout as in [[medieval]] times, one [[rod (length)|rod]] in width, the standard length for floor and roof [[joist]]s. The lanes along the north side of town are believed to follow the layout of the narrow medieval fields, and are slightly S-shaped because of the way ploughs turned at each end. Similar field boundaries can be seen in Warners Park.\n\n==Demography==\n===Population===\nIn the period 1801 to 1901 the population of St Ives was recorded every ten years by the [[Census in the United Kingdom|UK census]].  During this time the population was in the range of 2,099 (the lowest was in 1801) and 3,572 (the highest was in 1851).<ref name=Camin>{{cite web |title=Historic Census figures Cambridgeshire to 2011 |publisher=Cambridgeshire Insight |website=www.cambridgeshireinsight.org.uk |accessdate=12 February 2016 |url=http://www.cambridgeshireinsight.org.uk/file/2001/download |format=xlsx - download |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215102922/http://www.cambridgeshireinsight.org.uk/file/2001/download |archivedate=15 February 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1901, a census was taken every ten years with the exception of 1941 (due to the [[Second World War]]).\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size: 9pt\"\n|-\n!width=\"150\"|Parish<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1911<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1921<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1931<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1951<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1961<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1971<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1981<br>\n!width=\"30\"|1991<br>\n!width=\"30\"|2001<br>\n!width=\"30\"|2011 <br>\n|-\n|align=left|St Ives\n|align=\"center\"|3,015\n|align=\"center\"|2,797\n|align=\"center\"|2,664\n|align=\"center\"|3,078\n|align=\"center\"|4,082\n|align=\"center\"|7,148\n|align=\"center\"|12,331\n|align=\"center\"|14,930\n|align=\"center\"|16,001\n|align=\"center\"|16,384\n|-\n|}\n\n<small>\nAll population census figures from report ''Historic Census figures Cambridgeshire to 2011'' by ''Cambridgeshire Insight''.<ref name=Camin/>\n</small>\n\nIn 2011, the parish covered an area of {{convert|2688|acre|hectare|0}}<ref name=Camin/> and the population density of St Ives in 2011 was 3901 persons per square mile (1505.9 per square kilometre).\n\n==Economy==\nThe Monday market takes over the town centre, and is larger in scale on [[Bank Holiday]]s in May and August. There is a Friday market, and a [[Farmers' Market]] on the first and third Saturday every month. The [[Michaelmas]] Fair takes over for three days from the second Monday in October, and there is a carnival<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.stives-town.info/carnival/2006/2006_st_ives_carnival_parade.htm |title = The 2006 St Ives Carnival Parade}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.st-ives.info/fun/Carnival/ | title=St-ives.info}}</ref> which is the biggest public gathering in [[Huntingdonshire]]. The town has a mixture of shops, bars, coffee lounges, a department store and other amenities.\n\n==Public houses{{anchor|Golden Lion, St Ives}}==\n[[File:Market stalls in front of the Golden Lion Hotel, St Ives - geograph.org.uk - 310810.jpg|thumb|right|The Golden Lion, a former coaching inn]]\n\nAs an important market town, St Ives always needed large numbers of public houses, many of which were [[brothel|bawdy houses]]: 64 in 1838 (1 for every 55 inhabitants), 60 in 1861, 48 in 1865 and 45 in 1899, although only five of these made the owners a living. As livestock sales diminished, however, so did the need for large numbers of pubs, falling to a low point of 16 in 1962. In that year the ''Seven Wives'' on Ramsey Road was opened and, with some openings and closings since, there are 17 today. The oldest name is the ''Dolphin''; in use on the same site for over 300 years, it's current usage is for a hotel built in 1985. Next oldest is the ''White Hart'', which is pre-1720. ''Nelson's Head'' and ''Golden Lion'' are at least as old but have not kept the same name: they used to be called the ''Three Tuns'' and the ''Red Lion'' respectively. There has been a pub on the site of the ''Robin Hood'' from a similar date; in fact it was originally two separate pubs: the ''Angel'' and the ''Swan''. The claim of the Royal Oak to date from 1502 cannot be proven since, while a portion at the back is 17th-century (making it physically the oldest portion of any pub in St Ives), the pub name is more recent. The reference is to [[Charles II of England|Charles II]]'s famous escape from [[Oliver Cromwell|Cromwell]]'s [[Roundheads]], and Charles was restored to the throne in 1660.<ref>{{citation|title=The Pubs of St Ives|first=Bob|last=Burn-Murdoch|edition=3rd|publisher=Friends of the Norris Museum|date=16 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Golden Lion'' was a 19th-century [[coaching inn]].<ref name=fisher>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YWyrAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA151&dq=%22Golden+Lion%22 |title=British River Navigations: Inland Cuts, Fens, Dikes, Channels and Non-tidal Rivers |publisher=A&C Black |author=Stuart Fisher |year=2013 |page=151 |accessdate=29 July 2014|isbn=9781472906687 }}</ref> ''The Official Guide to the Great Eastern Railway'' referred to it in 1893 as one of two \"leading hotels\" in St Ives<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6MJRAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA271 |title=The Official Guide to the Great Eastern Railway |publisher=Cassell |author=Great Eastern Railway |year=1893 |page=271 |accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref> and there are a number of ghost stories associated with the pub.<ref name=fisher/><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EH-IAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT53&dq=%22Golden+Lion%22 |title=Paranormal Cambridgeshire |publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited |author=Damien O'Dell |year=2013 |page=53 |accessdate=29 July 2014|isbn=9781445629940 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KkqIAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT69&dq=%22Golden+Lion%22 |title=Military Ghosts |publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited |author=Alan Wood |year=2013 |page=69 |accessdate=29 July 2014|isbn=9781445625225 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a-nWAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Golden+Lion%22++%22St+Ives%22 |title=The International Directory of Haunted Places |publisher=Penguin Group |author=Dennis William Hauck |year=2000 |page=18 |accessdate=29 July 2014|isbn=9780140296358 }}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:St Ives, Cambridgeshire, England-7Aug2011.jpg|thumb|St Ives bridge and the River Great Ouse]]\n[[File:St Ives Cambs Oliver Cromwell statue.jpg|upright|thumb|The [[Statue of Oliver Cromwell, St Ives|Statue of Oliver Cromwell]] on Market Hill in the town centre]]\n\n===St Ives Bridge===\n{{Main|St Ives Bridge}}\nSt Ives Bridge is most unusual in incorporating a [[chapel]], the most striking of only four examples in England. Also unusual are its two southern arches which are a different shape from the rest of the bridge, being rounded instead of slightly [[gothic architecture|gothic]]. After the dissolution of the monasteries in 1537, the chapel was given to the prior to live in. The lords of the manor of St Ives changed hands several times, as did the chapel. During this period, it was in turn - a private house, a doctors surgery and a pub, called Little Hell. The pub had a reputation for rowdy behaviour, and it is believed the landlord kept pigs in the basement. The additional two storeys added in the seventeenth century were removed in 1930, due to damage being caused to the foundations. \nThe chapel features colourfully in the historical novel 'Not Just a Whore', by local St Ives resident K M Warwick, where it is described as a fictitious \"Bawdy House\" (brothel). The bridge was partially rebuilt after [[Oliver Cromwell]] knocked down two arches during the [[English Civil War]] to prevent [[Charles I of England|King Charles I's]] troops approaching London from the [[Cavalier|Royalist]] base in [[Lincolnshire]]. During the war and for some period afterwards, the gap was covered by a [[drawbridge]]. The town square contains a [[Statue of Oliver Cromwell, St Ives|statue of Oliver Cromwell]] erected in 1901. It is one of four statues of Cromwell on public display in Britain, the others being in [[Parliament Square]], outside [[Wythenshawe Hall]] and in [[Warrington]].\n\nSt Ives Corn Exchange is the home of St Ives Youth Theatre (SIYT).\n\n===Holt Island===\nThe eastern or town end of Holt Island is nature reserve, and the western end, opposite the parish church, is a facility for the Sea [[Scouts]]. The scout portion contains what was, before the opening of the Leisure Centre, the town's outdoor town swimming pool. The pool was dug in 1913 and closed to the public in 1949.<ref name=StIvesMillenium>{{cite news|title=St Ives a new Millenium|pages=8&ndash;9|newspaper=St Ives Photo Publication Group|publisher=Inchcape|year= 2002}}{{sic}}</ref> It is now used by the scouts for canoeing and rappelling. In November 1995, the island was the locus of a significant lawsuit and a break-away Scouting Association was prevented from using and developing a claim to it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lgcplus.com/news/scouts-fight-for-right-to-island/1563962.article|title=SCOUTS FIGHT FOR RIGHT TO ISLAND|work=[[Local Government Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Emap Communications]]|date=19 November 1995|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Culture and community==\nThe Norris Museum holds a great deal of local history, including a number of books written by its former curator, Bob Burn-Murdoch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norrismuseum.org.uk/ |title=Norris Museum |publisher=Norris Museum. |date= |accessdate=2012-06-11}}</ref>  After over 30 years of service, Bob Burn-Murdoch retired in December 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Ives museum comes to an end of an era|url=http://www.huntspost.co.uk/news/latest-news/st_ives_museum_comes_to_end_of_an_era_as_curator_announces_retirement_1_1475853|accessdate=17 March 2013|newspaper=Hunts Post|date=9 August 2012}}</ref> \nThe Norris Museum was founded by Herbert Norris, who left his lifetime's collection of Huntingdonshire relics to the people of St Ives when he died in 1931.It has recently been reopened in August 2017, following a \u00a31.5m refurbishment and expansion made possible by a Heritage Lottery Fund grant. Its current director is Sarah Russell, and it is managed by the Norris Management Trust, made up of members of St Ives Town Council and the Friends of the Norris Museum.\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:St ives rowing club.jpg|thumb|Boathouse of St Ives Rowing Club]]\nThere are 2 leisure facilities, the indoor centre is adjacent to the Burgess conference and Events Hall and an outdoor centre in the west of the town. The original swimming pool, fed by the river, is in the middle of Holt Island and is now used for canoeing practice and other activities. St Ives also has a [[Rugby union|Rugby]] club on Somersham Road,<ref>{{cite web|last=Kirby |first=Andy |url=http://www.stivesrufc.co.uk |title=St Ives Rugby Union Football Club |publisher=Stivesrufc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-06-11}}</ref> and a [[Non-League football]] club, [[St Ives Town F.C.]], which plays at Westwood Road.  The St Ives Rowing Club was once captained by [[John Goldie (barrister)|John Goldie]] and has had a number of members who have competed at Olympic and Commonwealth championships.\n\nThere is an active swimming club. New members are always welcome, from age 4\u00bd upwards, whatever their swimming ability and can be slotted into (and trained up to) teaching groups, a pre-competitive group, development squads or senior/competitive squads [http://www.stivesswimclub.co.uk]\n\nSt Ives has an 18 hole championship golf course, located 1/2 mile east of St Ives on the A1123. It opened in the summer of 2010, replacing the previous 9 hole course on Westwood Road/ High Leys. \n[http://www.stivesgolfclub.co.uk/]\n\nEach year the town hosts a free 2 day carnival and music festival which was launched in 1999, as part of the committee set up for the millennium. This is now part of the towns tradition and it grows year on year.\n\n==Education==\nSt Ives has a main [[secondary school]], [[St Ivo School]]. Eastfield nursery and infant school, Westfield Junior school and two [[primary school]]s Thorndown and Wheatfields.\nIn 2018, a plan was announced to combine and expand Eastfield and Westfield in to one larger community primary school.\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Guided busway===\n{{Main|Cambridgeshire Guided Busway}}\nThe major section of the world's longest guided busway, using all new construction techniques and technology, connects St Ives directly to [[Cambridge Science Park]] on the outskirts of [[Cambridge]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/db/pressrel.nsf/cac74a2aba838b5d80256b56004e53ab/edcbd21f6a9cf5b880257295004c237b?OpenDocument|title=Secretary Of State Celebrates Start Of Works On Guided Busway|publisher=[[Cambridgeshire County Council]]|date=5 March 2007|accessdate=6 September 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090606040816/http://www2.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/db/pressrel.nsf/cac74a2aba838b5d80256b56004e53ab/edcbd21f6a9cf5b880257295004c237b?OpenDocument|archivedate=6 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> along the route of a disused railway line. The same buses continue into the centre of Cambridge along regular roads in one direction and continue to [[Huntingdon]] in the other direction. A shorter section of the same busway system operates from the [[Cambridge railway station|railway station]] on the far side of Cambridge to [[Addenbrooke's Hospital]] and [[Trumpington, Cambridgeshire|Trumpington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/transport/guided/|title=The Busway Network|publisher=[[Cambridgeshire County Council]]|accessdate=6 September 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416144840/http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/transport/guided/|archivedate=16 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The scheme, budgeted at \u00a3116.2 million, opened in summer 2011. Construction of the busway was beset with problems, causing delays; for example, cracks appeared in the structure allowing weeds to grow through. Contractors BAM Nuttall were fined a significant amount of money for each day that the busway completion date was not met.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/40F67C0E-CB57-4327-A7BE-440650E8B822/0/CGBleafletweb.pdf|title=Cambridgeshire Guided Busway - Information about the scheme|publisher=[[Cambridgeshire County Council]]|date=10 January 2007|accessdate=6 September 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528012536/http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/40F67C0E-CB57-4327-A7BE-440650E8B822/0/CGBleafletweb.pdf|archivedate=28 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe St Ives [[Park & Ride]] on Meadow Lane is part of the scheme and will open at the same time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/346A6FC8-8095-471B-88CB-41DCAB168459/0/GBnewsletterOct08hires.pdf |title=Guided Busway Update |date=October 2008 |publisher=[[Cambridgeshire County Council]] |accessdate=6 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609185118/http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/346A6FC8-8095-471B-88CB-41DCAB168459/0/GBnewsletterOct08hires.pdf |archivedate=9 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> A \"Green Update\" newsletter came out in Winter 2007 with news on conservation work including protection of the Great Crested Newt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3D59D72B-2A13-49A7-869E-62DB5CDC0629/0/CGBGreenUpdate.pdf |title=Guided Busway Green Update - Winter 2007 |date=26 November 2007 |accessdate=6 September 2009 |publisher=[[cambridgeshire County Council]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609185202/http://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/3D59D72B-2A13-49A7-869E-62DB5CDC0629/0/CGBGreenUpdate.pdf |archivedate=9 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Road===\nSt Ives is just off the [[A14 road (England)|A14]] road on a particularly congested section of the route from the [[UK]]'s second city, [[Birmingham]], to the port of [[Felixstowe]] and thence to the mainland of [[Europe]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teletrac.net/__assets/ksrwvo1ouk6smobtjr.pdf|title=Trafficmaster/RAC Foundation Congestion report: Volume 2|page=9|publisher=Trafficmaster plc and RAC Foundation for Motoring|accessdate=6 September 2009}}{{Dead link|date=September 2009}}</ref> This {{convert|32|km|adj=on}} section of road also links the northern end of the M11 ([[Cambridge]] and region) to the [[M1 motorway (England)|M1]] and the whole of the [[North of England]] and [[Scotland]]. A new by-pass is planned for St Ives and [[Huntingdon]], leaving the existing alignment near [[Swavesey]] and passing to the south of both market towns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/documents/A14_Ellington_to_Fen_Ditton_Public_Exhibition_Leaflet.pdf |title=Ellington to Fen Ditton Improvemebt |date=November 2008 |accessdate=6 September 2009 |publisher=[[Highways Agency]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605141735/http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/documents/A14_Ellington_to_Fen_Ditton_Public_Exhibition_Leaflet.pdf |archivedate=5 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> A northern bypass has been under discussion for even longer but is not anticipated any time soon.\n\n===Rail and conventional bus===\nBus services are provided by Stagecoach in Huntingdonshire and Go Whippet, the former also having its depot near the town. Services to [[Cambridge]] and [[Huntingdon]] are frequent during the day, though less frequent in the evenings.  There are also buses to Somersham, Ramsey and Cambourne.\n\nBetween 1847 and 1970 the town was served by [[St Ives (Cambridgeshire) railway station|St Ives railway station]] on the [[Cambridge and Huntingdon railway]].<ref name=subbrit>{{cite web|url=http://www.subbrit.org.uk/sb-sites/stations/s/st.ives/index.shtml|title=Station Name:ST. IVES (Huntingdonshire)|publisher=www.subbrit.org.uk|accessdate=29 October 2008|first=Nick|last=Catford}}</ref> The line from Cambridge and the station almost survived the 1963 to 1973 [[Beeching Axe]], but were lost to passenger service in the final stages of the process. Some sections continued to be used for freight until 1993. A campaign to reopen the passenger rail service only ended with the ripping-up of disused track shortly before construction of the Guided Busway. Huntingdon, {{convert|7|mile|km}}) away, has the nearest railway station. Buses using the Busway system provide direct links to both Huntingdon and Cambridge stations.\n\n==Religious sites==\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2016}}\n[[File:cmglee_St_Ives_All_Saints_Parish_Church.jpg|thumb|upright|All Saints parish church, May 2014.]]\n[[File:cmglee St Ives Market Hill.jpg|thumb|upright|The Free Church and Market Hill.]]\nThere are ten places of worship, including the ancient [[parish church]]. Many other Christian denominations are also represented, and the town also has a [[mosque]] and an [[Islamic]] Community Centre.\n\nAll Saints Church ([[Church of England]]) on Church Street has been in the town since AD970 and is one of only two [[Grade I listed building]]s in the town, the other being The Bridge. Originally the parish church of the settlement of Slepe, before St Ives came into existence, it now enjoys a tranquil location at the end of Church Street, situated to the west of the town centre. All Saints, as it stands today, dates largely from the rebuilding of the late 15th century. It was extensively reordered in the late 19th century by [[Ninian Comper|Sir Ninian Comper]].\n\nThe church which dominates the town's market place, is The Free Church ([[United Reformed Church]]). This was built in 1864, but was modernised in 1980, moving the worship area upstairs. The [[Sacred Heart Church, St Ives|Church of the Sacred Heart]] ([[Roman Catholic]]) on Needingworth Road, was originally built by [[Augustus Pugin]] in Cambridge, but was dismantled in 1902 and transported by barge to St Ives. The hall at the back was added in about 2001. The current [[Methodist Church]] on The Waits opened in 1905. Crossways Church ([[Assembly of God]]) meet at Crossways Christian Centre on Ramsey Road. St Ives Christian Fellowship (Partnership) meet at Thorndown Junior School on Hill Rise. The Bridge Church (New Frontiers) meet in a newly renovated former industrial building on the corner of Burrel Road and Marley Road. St Ives Evangelical Christian Church ([[Evangelicalism|Evangelical]]) meet at the Burleigh Hill Community Centre, off Constable Road.\n\n==Cultural references==\n[[File:St Ives Seven Wives PH At Night.jpg|thumb|The Seven Wives pub on a summer's night]] \nThe town name is featured in the anonymous nursery rhyme/riddle \"[[As I was going to St Ives]]\". While sometimes claimed to be [[St Ives, Cornwall]], the man with seven wives, each with seven sacks containing seven cats etc. may have been on his way to (or coming from) the [[fair|Great Fair]] at St Ives.<ref>{{citation |title=St Ives, Slepe by the Ouse |first=Noel |last=Hudson |year=1989 |page=131 |publisher=St Ives Town Council |isbn=978-0-9515298-0-5}}</ref> On Ramsey Road there is a [[public house]] called The Seven Wives, though this is a modern pub with no connection to the ancient rhyme other than the name.<ref>Indeed in the earliest recorded English version of the riddle, of 1730, there were nine wives. See main article.</ref>\n\nThe term '''tawdry''' is a St Ives derived word (vying with the rival Ely claim), basically meaning something that is 'cheap and cheerful', and was evolved directly from the St Audrey's Lane cloth market held during the mediaeval and later ages.  Made from discarded inferior wool and/or other felt fibres, it was a popular source of cheap material bought by the locals, and those further afield, who flocked to the market in their droves to buy cheap supplies for their own domestic clothing.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe famous war poet [[Rupert Brooke]] lived at [[Grantchester]] some {{convert|32|km|mi}} away in the same [[county]]. In his famous poem \"''[[The Old Vicarage, Grantchester]]''\" he heaped praise on his own village, but not on the [[shire town]] of [[Cambridge]] itself, or on the other villages around. Of St Ives he wrote:\n{{cquote|Strong men have blanched and shot their wives, rather than send them to St Ives<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.orchard-grantchester.com/poetry.html|title=The Old Vicarage, Grantchester|first=Rupert|last=Brooke|place=Caf\u00e9 des Westerns, Berlin|date=May 1912|accessdate=21 March 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302153404/http://www.orchard-grantchester.com/poetry.html|archivedate=2 March 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n''St Ives, Slepe by the Ouse'', by Noel Hudson. Black Bear Press, 1989, {{ISBN|0-9515298-0-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n* [http://www.stivestowncouncil.gov.uk/ St Ives Town Council web-site]\n\n{{River Great Ouse|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Ives, Cambridgeshire}}\n[[Category:St Ives, Cambridgeshire| ]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Huntingdonshire]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the River Great Ouse]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Towns in Cambridgeshire]]\n", "name_user": "Thejpster", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correct 'major' to 'Mayor' and link to Mayors in England", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Ives,_Cambridgeshire"}
{"title_page": "List of Top Country Albums number ones of 1995", "text_new": "[[File:JMM1862004-06-18.jpg|thumb|right|250px|alt=Singer John Michael Montogmery|[[John Michael Montgomery]] spent 13 consecutive weeks at number one with [[John Michael Montgomery (album)|his eponymous album]].]] \n[[Top Country Albums]] is a [[record chart|chart]] that ranks the top-performing [[country music]] albums in the United States, published by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.  In 1995, seven different albums topped the chart, based on sales reports submitted by a representative sample of stores nationwide.<ref>{{cite book|title=Joel Whitburn Presents Hot Country Albums: Billboard 1964 to 2007|first=Joel|last=Whitburn|publisher=Record Research, Incorporated|date=2008|isbn=9780898201734|page=6}}</ref>\n\nIn the issue of ''Billboard'' dated January 7, [[Garth Brooks]] was at number one with the compilation album ''[[The Hits (Garth Brooks album)|The Hits]]'', its second week in the top spot.<ref name=J7 />  The album held the peak position for the first 14 weeks of 1995 and returned to number one for a single week later in the year; its 16 weeks atop the chart took Brooks's total number of weeks in the top spot to 113 in less than five years.<ref>{{cite book|title=Joel Whitburn Presents Hot Country Albums: Billboard 1964 to 2007|first=Joel|last=Whitburn|publisher=Record Research, Incorporated|date=2008|isbn=9780898201734|page=40}}</ref>  The singer returned to number one in December with his next album ''[[Fresh Horses (album)|Fresh Horses]]'', which held the top spot for the final four weeks of the year; he was the only artist to achieve more than one chart-topper during 1995.  ''The Hits'' was the only one of 1995's Top Country Albums number ones to also top the all-genre [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart.\n\nIn July, [[Shania Twain]] gained her first number one with ''[[The Woman in Me (Shania Twain album)|The Woman in Me]]''; the album spent 11 weeks in the top spot in 1995 but would return to number one for a further 18 weeks the following year, making it the longest-running number one country album to date by a female artist.<ref>{{cite book|title=Joel Whitburn Presents Hot Country Albums: Billboard 1964 to 2007|first=Joel|last=Whitburn|publisher=Record Research, Incorporated|date=2008|isbn=9780898201734|page=256}}</ref>  The album launched the Canadian singer to stardom in both the country and pop markets, and helped to make her one of the most successful recording artists of the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/shania-twain-mn0000161808/biography|title=Shania Twain Biography & History|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewin|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Chart history==\n[[File:Garth Brooks at We Are One (edit).jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Singer Garth Brooks|[[Garth Brooks]] both began and ended the year at number one.]]\n[[File:ShaniaTwain1.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Singer Shania Twain|[[Shania Twain]] reached number one for the first time with ''[[The Woman in Me (Shania Twain album)|The Woman in Me]]''.]]\n[[File:Alan Jackson (3023584051).jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=Singer Alan Jackson|[[Alan Jackson]] topped the chart with ''[[The Greatest Hits Collection (Alan Jackson album)|The Greatest Hits Collection]]''.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=col|Issue date\n!scope=col|Title\n!scope=col|Artist(s)\n!scope=col class=unsortable|Ref.\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|January 7}}\n|rowspan=\"14\"|''{{sort|Hits|[[The Hits (Garth Brooks album)|The Hits]]}}''\n|rowspan=\"14\"| {{sortname|Garth|Brooks}}\n|align=center|<ref name=J7>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/country-albums/1995-01-07|title=Country Albums chart for January 7, 1995|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row|{{dts|January 14}}\n|align=center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/country-albums/1995-01-14|title=Countr