{"title_page": "Joachim V", "text_new": "{{Infobox Patriarch\n|name= Joachim V Daw\n|image=\n|church=Greek Orthodox [[Church of Antioch]]\n|see=[[Patriarch of Antioch]]\n|patriarch_of=[[List of Greek Orthodox Patriarchs of Antioch|Patriarch of Antioch]]\n|enthroned=1581\n|ended=1592\n|predecessor=[[Michael VI (Sabbagh)]]\n|successor=[[Joachim VI]]\n|death_date=1592}}\n\nPatriarch '''Joachim V''' (died 1592) was [[Greek Orthodox]] [[Patriarch of Antioch]] from 1581 to 1592.\n\n==Life==\n\nUpon the death of Patriarch Joachim IV in 1576, the Orthodox bishops of Syria selected Joachim V (then Metropolitan Dorotheus of Tripoli), Metropolitan Macarius of Euchaita, and Metropolitan Gregorius of Aleppo as the three most worthy candidates to succeed him, and tasked the three with deciding among themselves who should become patriarch. Gregorius, who did not want to abandon his see due to his popularity and political strength in Aleppo, voted for Macarius, and Dorotheus did the same.\n\nMacarius, who took the name Michael upon his enthronement, resigned in 1581 under intense pressure from the Orthodox community of Damascus, where the seat of the patriarchate was located. The Damascenes asked Joachim to become the next patriarch, and he accepted. However, Michael soon retracted his abdication, and the two both claimed to be the rightful patriarch until 1583, when Michael abdicated a second time.\n\nDuring the feud with Michael, Joachim was forced to spend huge sums of money to buy support from both Church and governmental authorities. In particular, Joachim promised the rulers of Damascus and Tripoli (two very important centers of the patriarchate) large sums of money to support him, but found soon after that he could not afford to pay the promised amounts. In fear for his life, the patriarch briefly went into hiding in the mountains of modern Lebanon before journeying to Constantinople to seek financial aid from the wealthy Greeks of the capital. When such support proved insufficient, Joachim went on an alms-gathering trip to Russia between 1585 and 1587. The trip was successful, and when he returned to Damascus, he paid off his debts and had more than enough left over to solidify his fragile authority over all the Orthodox bishops of Syria. For the remainder of his term as patriarch, his main assistant was Metropolitan Anastasius of Triploli, Beirut, Tyre, and Sidon.<ref name=\"Skaff\">{{cite book|last=Panchenko|first=Constantin|title= Arab Orthodox Christians under the Ottomans: 1516-1831| publisher= Holy Trinity Seminary Press|year= 2016|pages=164-65}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Greek Orthodox Patriarchs of Antioch]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joachim V}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:1592 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Patriarch\n|name= Joachim V Daw\n|image=\n|church=Greek Orthodox [[Church of Antioch]]\n|see=[[Patriarch of Antioch]]\n|patriarch_of=[[List of Greek Orthodox Patriarchs of Antioch|Patriarch of Antioch]]\n|enthroned=1581\n|ended=1592\n|predecessor=[[Michael VI (Sabbagh)]]\n|successor=[[Joachim VI]]\n|death_date=1592}}\n\nPatriarch '''Joachim V''' (died 1592) was [[Greek Orthodox]] [[Patriarch of Antioch]] from 1581 to 1592.\n\n==Life==\n\nUpon the death of Patriarch Joachim IV in 1576, the Orthodox bishops of Syria selected Joachim V (then Metropolitan Dorotheus of Tripoli), Metropolitan Macarius of Euchaita, and Metropolitan Gregorius of Aleppo as the three most worthy candidates to succeed him, and tasked the three with deciding among themselves who should become patriarch. Gregorius, who did not want to abandon his see due to his popularity and political strength in Aleppo, voted for Macarius, and Dorotheus did the same.\n\nMacarius, who took the name Michael upon his enthronement, resigned in 1581 under intense pressure from the Orthodox community of Damascus, where the seat of the patriarchate was located. The Damascenes asked Joachim to become the next patriarch, and he accepted. However, Michael soon retracted his abdication, and the two both claimed to be the rightful patriarch until until 1583, when Michael abdicated a second time.\n\nDuring the feud with Michael, Joachim was forced to spend huge sums of money to buy support from both Church and governmental authorities. In particular, Joachim promised the rulers of Damascus and Tripoli (two very important centers of the patriarchate) large sums of money to support him, but found soon after that he could not afford to pay the promised amounts. In fear for his life, the patriarch briefly went into hiding in the mountains of modern Lebanon before journeying to Constantinople to seek financial aid from the wealthy Greeks of the capital. When such support proved insufficient, Joachim went on an alms-gathering trip to Russia between 1585 and 1587. The trip was successful, and when he returned to Damascus, he paid off his debts and had more than enough left over to solidify his fragile authority over all the Orthodox bishops of Syria. For the remainder of his term as patriarch, his main assistant was Metropolitan Anastasius of Triploli, Beirut, Tyre, and Sidon.<ref name=\"Skaff\">{{cite book|last=Panchenko|first=Constantin|title= Arab Orthodox Christians under the Ottomans: 1516-1831| publisher= Holy Trinity Seminary Press|year= 2016|pages=164-65}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Greek Orthodox Patriarchs of Antioch]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joachim V}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:1592 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joachim_V"}
{"title_page": "David Broncano", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = David Broncano\n| image              = Premios Goya 2019 - David Broncano.jpg\n| image_size         = 240px\n| alias              ={{flatlist|\n*El Pachangas<ref>{{cite tweet |user=paugasol |author-link=Pau Gasol |number=1248009766107922433 |date=April 8, 2020 |title=\u00a1Grande, Pachangas!}}</ref>\n*Mes\u00edas de Ja\u00e9n<ref>{{cite news |title=El \" Friky de Ja\u00e9n\" tiene p\u00falpito libre en 0# Movistar Televisi\u00f3n |url=http://www.diariojaen.es/portada/arrobas-de-ingenio-FC2253878 |date=26 October 2016 |access-date=13 February 2018 |newspaper=Diario Ja\u00e9n |last=Serrano Alba |first=Jos\u00e9 Manuel |language=es}}</ref>\n*Pachacho\n*Danger Oil\n*Aceite Peligroso\n*sweaty brother\n}}\n| caption            = David Broncano in 2019\n| birth_name         = David Broncano Aguilera\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1985|12|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Santiago de Compostela]], [[A Coru\u00f1a]]\n| nationality        = {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Spaniard|Spanish]]\n| occupation         = [[Comedian]] and [[television host]]\n| years_active       = 2008-present\n| website            = {{url|www.davidbroncano.com}}\n}}\n\n'''David Broncano Aguilera''' ([[Santiago de Compostela]], 30 December 1985)<ref>{{Citation|title=David Broncano|date=2019-04-20|url=https://es.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=David_Broncano&oldid=115396416|work=Wikipedia, la enciclopedia libre|language=es|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref> is a Spanish [[comedian]] and [[television host]]. He has also worked in [[news agency|news]] and [[advertising agency|advertising agencies]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ideal.es/jaen/jaen/201702/06/embajador-orcera-20170206003656-v.html |title=El 'embajador' de Orcera |last=Contreras |first=Miguel \u00c1ngel |date=6 February 2017 |access-date=21 August 2018 |newspaper=[[Ideal (newspaper)|Ideal]] |language=es |publisher=[[Vocento]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elperiodico.com/es/mas-periodico/20160131/david-broncano-tengo-espiritu-bufon-troll-internet-4850974 |title=David Broncano: \"Tengo un esp\u00edritu de buf\u00f3n, como de troll de internet\" |last=Mart\u00ednez |first=Beatriz |date=31 January 2016 |access-date=21 August 2018 |newspaper=[[El Peri\u00f3dico de Catalunya]] |language=es |publisher=Grupo Zeta}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 he was awarded the \"Ja\u00e9n, Para\u00edso Interior\" award by the Provincial Council of [[Province of Murcia|Murcia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.20jaenparaiso.dipujaen.es/index.php/2017/09/29/premios-jaen-paraiso-interior/ |title=Premios \"Ja\u00e9n, Para\u00edso Interior\" |access-date=18 January 2018 |work=Diputaci\u00f3n de Ja\u00e9n |date=29 September 2017 |language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123032102/http://20jaenparaiso.dipujaen.es/index.php/2017/09/29/premios-jaen-paraiso-interior/ |archive-date=23 January 2018 |url-status = dead}}</ref> Furthermore, he won two [[Ondas Awards]] for the program \"La Vida Moderna\" [The modern life] in the category of best national radio program in 2018<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ondas Awards |title=PREMIOS ONDAS NACIONALES DE RADIO |url=https://www.premiosondas.com/historia_2019-2010-18.php |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> and for the late night show \"La Resistencia\" [The resilience] in the category of Best light entertainment program on television in 2019<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ondas Awards |title=AWARD-WINNERS 2019 |url=https://www.premiosondas.com/en/premiados.php |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>. \n\nSince 2018 he hosts, with Ricardo Castella, the late night television show ''La Resistencia'', on [[Movistar+]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.europapress.es/tv/noticia-david-broncano-presentara-resistencia-nuevo-late-show-movistar-20180119163002.html |title=David Broncano presentar\u00e1 La Resistencia, el nuevo late show de Movistar+ |date=19 January 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |newspaper=[[Europa Press (news agency)|Europa Press]] |location=Madrid |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.20minutos.es/noticia/3239378/0/david-broncano-presentara-resistencia-nuevo-late-show-movistar/ |title=David Broncano presentar\u00e1 La Resistencia, el nuevo late show de Movistar+ |author=Europa Press |author-link=Europa Press (news agency) |date=19 January 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |newspaper=[[20 Minutos]] |language=es}}</ref> The first season finished on 5 July 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://as.com/epik/2018/07/06/portada/1530889834_154224.html |title=Broncano despide la temporada de La Resistencia por todo lo alto con Yung Beef |author=Epik |date=6 July 2018 |access-date=7 September 2018 |newspaper=[[AS (newspaper)|AS]] |language=es}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Date\n! Program\n! Channel\n|-\n| 2018-actualidad\n| ''La Resistencia''\n| rowspan=3| [[Cero (TV channel)|#0]]\n|-\n| 2016-2017\n| ''Loco Mundo''\n|-\n| 2016-2018\n| ''[[Late Motiv]]''\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''El club de los poetas muertos''\n| [[La Sexta]]\n|-\n| 2009\n|''Ilustres ignorantes''\n| [[Canal+ 1]], [[Cero (TV channel)|#0]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Yutubers''\n| [[Comedy Central (Spain)|Comedy Central]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Sopa de gansos''\n| [[Cuatro (TV channel)|Cuatro]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Alguien ten\u00eda que decirlo''\n| [[La Sexta]]\n|-\n| 2011-2012\n| ''\u00d3xido Nitroso''\n| [[Canal+ 1]]\n|-\n| 2011-2012\n| ''Tentaciones''\n| [[Canal+ 1]]\n|-\n| 2010-2011\n| ''Nos gusta el cine''\n| [[Canal+ 1]]\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''UAU!''\n| rowspan=2| [[Cuatro (TV channel)|Cuatro]]\n|-\n| 2008-2009\n| ''Estas no son las noticias''\n|-\n| 2008-2009\n| ''Nuevos C\u00f3micos''\n| [[Comedy Central (Spain)|Comedy Central]]\n|}\n\n=== Radio ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Program\n! Station\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''La vida moderna''\n| rowspan=2| [[Cadena SER]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''A vivir que son dos d\u00edas''\n|-\n| 2015-2016\n| ''Anda Ya''\n| rowspan=2| [[Los 40]]\n|-\n| 