{"title_page": "Deliveroo", "text_new": "{{short description|Food delivery company}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Roofoods Ltd.\n| logo = Deliveroo logo.svg\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| trade_name = Deliveroo\n| industry = {{Unbulleted list|[[Online food ordering]]|[[Food delivery]]}}\n| founder = [[Will Shu]]\n| hq_location = London, England, UK\n| area_served = {{Unbulleted list|[[United Kingdom]]|[[Netherlands]]|[[France]]|[[Belgium]]|[[Hong Kong]]|[[Ireland]]|[[Spain]]|[[Italy]]|[[Australia]]|[[Singapore]]|[[Kuwait]]|[[Puerto Rico]]|[[United Arab Emirates]]}}\n| key_people = Will Shu ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]]) <br> Greg Orlowski <br> Dan Winn ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]]) <br> Rohan Pradhan ([[Chief operating officer|COO]])\n| products = \n| revenue = \u00a3277.1 M (2017) <ref>{{Citation|title=Deliveroo profile |work=Craft |url=https://craft.co/deliveroo|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n| num_employees = 5,699 (2019)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://craft.co/deliveroo|title=Deliveroo Company Profile |publisher=Craft|accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n* Around 20,000 technically self-employed couriers ({{As of|2016|9|lc=y}})<ref name=\"When-your-boss-is-an-algorithm\" />\n| website = {{url|deliveroo.co.uk}}\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2013}}\n}}\n\n'''Roofoods Ltd.''' (branded as '''Deliveroo''') is an online [[food delivery]] company founded in 2013 by [[Will Shu]] and Greg Orlowski.<ref name=Deliverooleaflet /> Based in [[London]], England, it operates in two hundred cities<ref name=Sassard2017 /> in the United Kingdom, the Netherlands, France, Belgium, Ireland, Spain, Italy, Australia, Singapore, United Arab Emirates, Hong Kong, and Kuwait. A subsidiary operation, '''Deliveroo Editions''', focuses on developing a network of [[ghost kitchen]]s\u2014kitchens located off-site from restaurants for the preparation of delivery-only meals.<ref name=\"Sawera, VB, Deliveroo, 4/5/2017\">{{cite web |last1=Sawers |first1=Paul |title=Food courier Deliveroo launches platform for restaurants to open delivery-only kitchens |url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/04/05/food-courier-deliveroo-launches-platform-for-restaurants-to-open-delivery-only-kitchens/ |website=VentureBeat.com |accessdate=17 June 2019 |date=April 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Business==\n===History and basic operations===\nThe company Deliveroo, headquartered in London, was founded in 2013 by Will Shu and Greg Orlowski, both Americans.<ref name=Deliverooleaflet>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/information_society/newsroom/image/document/2016-6/deliveroo_13855.pdf|title=Introduction to Deliveroo|date=4 February 2016|access-date=12 November 2016|website=European Commission|author=Deliveroo}}</ref> The company makes money by charging restaurants a commission fee, as well as by charging customers a fee per order.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/parmyolson/2016/02/17/deliveroo-army-5000-drivers-3-years/|title=Here's How Deliveroo Built An Army Of 5,000 Drivers In Just 3 Years|first=Parmy|last=Olson|work=Forbes|date=17 February 2016|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref> It operates in two hundred cities<ref name=Sassard2017>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/deliveroo-fundraising/uks-deliveroo-raises-nearly-500-mln-ahead-of-200th-city-launch-idUSL8N1NN4JE|title=UK's Deliveroo raises nearly $500 mln ahead of 200th city launch |first=Sophie|last=Sassard |date=17 November 2017 |publisher=Reuters|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref> in the [[UK]], and in the [[Netherlands]], [[France]], [[Belgium]], [[Ireland]], [[Spain]], [[Italy]], [[Australia]], [[Singapore]], [[United Arab Emirates]], [[Kuwait]] and [[Hong Kong]].\n\nOrders are placed through its app or website and then [[self-employed]]<ref name=Beeger2016>{{cite news |url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/menschen-wirtschaft/vor-und-nachteile-der-gig-economy-14357206.html|title=Die Chancen der \"Gig-Economy\". Digitalisierter Arbeitsmarkt |trans-title=The Chances of the Gig Economy, digitized labour market |date=26 July 2016|access-date=14 November 2016|first=Britta|last=Beeger|newspaper=Frankfurter Allgemeine |language=German |quote=Und auch der Essenslieferdienst Deliveroo, der derzeit Fahrer mit gro\u00dfen Thermo-Rucks\u00e4cken durch die Gro\u00dfst\u00e4dte schickt, sucht seinen Stellenausschreibungen zufolge Fahrer, die selbst\u00e4ndig oder auf Midijobbasis t\u00e4tig sind. English: And the delivery service Deliveroo, which currently sends drivers with large thermo-backpacks through the cities, looking for job advertisements according to drivers who operate independently or on a Midi-job basis.}}</ref> [[Bicycle courier|bicycle]] or [[motorcycle courier|motorcycle]] couriers transport orders from restaurants to customers.\n\nIn November 2017 Deliveroo introduced Deliveroo Plus, a subscription service which gives customers in the UK unlimited free delivery<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/deliveroos-subscription-service-is-now-available-across-the-uk-2017-11?r=US&IR=T|title=Deliveroo's \u00a37.99 a month subscription service is now available across the UK|first=Sam|last=Shead|date=8 November 2017|publisher=BusinessInsider|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nDeliveroo works with some of the biggest chain restaurants across the UK, with the majority being available exclusively on the Deliveroo app along with thousands of independent restaurants.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deliveroo.co.uk/sitemap/|title=Deliveroo Sitemap|publisher=Deliveroo|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.deliveroo.co.uk/news/death-of-the-lunchbox.html|title=Death of the Lunchbox?|date=24 April 2017|publisher=Deliveroo|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref> On 16 November 2016, it became known that the brewing company [[Heineken International]] had closed a deal for Deliveroo to deliver the latter's beers and ciders, initially across 15 sites in London, Bath and Cardiff. This delivery deal, whose activities started that same week, was considered the biggest one of its kind (that is, with regards to the brewing industry). Further expansion of these activities across the UK were planned by the end of the year 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/11/16/heineken-joins-deliveroo-to-create-booze-delivery-brand/|title=Heineken joins Deliveroo to create booze delivery brand|series=Business|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=16 November 2016|access-date=18 November 2016|first=Jillian|last=Ambrose}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.beveragedaily.com/Retail-Shopper-Insights/Deliveroo-Heineken-partner-on-beer-delivery-brand|title=Deliveroo and Heineken partner to launch beer delivery brand|newspaper=Beverage Daily|first=Rachel|last=Arthur|date=17 November 2016|access-date=18 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Deliveroo announced plans to create 300 UK tech jobs when it opens its new head office in London later in 2017. Also in January 2017, the British-born company employed more than 1,000 full-time staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-38659329|title=Deliveroo to add 300 UK tech jobs in new London office|work=BBC News|date=18 January 2017|access-date=18 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nDeliveroo\u2019s Editions kitchens launched in April 2017. These delivery-only kitchens, sometimes known as [[ghost restaurant]]s, allow restaurants to access customers in locations without needing [[High Street]] premises, thereby reducing set-up costs compared to a full-service restaurant. Deliveroo uses its data to identify areas where customer demand for certain cuisines is high and predicts which restaurants are likely to succeed there.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/04/05/deliveroo-opens-30-kitchens-meet-surging-takeaway-demand/|title=Deliveroo opens 30 kitchens to meet surging takeaway demand|first=James|last=Titcomb|date=5 April 2017|publisher=Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1e516472-1a11-11e7-a266-12672483791a|title=Deliveroo expands with standalone takeaway kitchens|first=Madhumita|last=Murgia|date=5 April 2017|publisher=Financial Times|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-June 2016, the founders of Deliveroo, Will Shu and Greg Orlowski received an award for the \"Best Startup Founders\" as part of \"The Europas Startup Conference and Awards\", which are given to [[Technology company|technology companies]]. The company also received Fastest Rising Startup of the Year and the Europas Grand Prix award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/06/17/the-europas-awards-2016-honored-the-best-tech-startups-in-europe/|title=The Europas Awards 2016 honored the best tech startups in Europe|first=Mike|last=Butcher|date=17 June 2016|publisher=TechCrunch|access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nDeliveroo recorded a loss of \u00a31.4m for the year 2015. Mid-November 2016, the company reported a loss of \u00a318.1 million for that year. In September 2017 Deliveroo recorded a growth in global revenue of 611% in 2016, with sales of \u00a3128.6 million, while \"losses soared from \u00a330.1m to \u00a3129.1m\".<ref name=\"Deliveroo-boss-doubled-his-pau-ahead-of-riders\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/nov/11/deliveroo-boss-pay-ahead-riders-protest|title=Deliveroo boss doubled his pay ahead of riders' protest |newspaper=The Guardian|date=11 November 2016|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Fury-as-Deliveroo-boss-nearly-doubles-his-pay-while-his-workers-fight\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/markets/article-3928578/Fury-Deliveroo-boss-nearly-doubles-pay-workers-fight-better-wages.html |title=Fury as Deliveroo boss nearly doubles his pay while his workers fight for better wages|date=11 November 2016|access-date=12 November 2016|newspaper=This is MONEY}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/09/21/deliveroo-revenues-grow-600pc-losses-stack/|title=Deliveroo revenues grow over 600pc but losses stack up |first=James|last=Titcomb|date=21 September 2017|publisher=Daily Telegraph |access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Deliveroo Rider Taking The Lane In Bristol (32611782273).jpg|thumb|Deliveroo cyclist in the UK]]\nDeliveroo provides the delivery service as well as [[marketing]] and order taking, allowing it to provide food from restaurants that do not normally offer a delivery service. In a press release of May 2016, the German Bar Association ({{lang-de|Der Deutsche Anwaltverein}}) informed the public that delivery companies such as Deliveroo, Take Eat Easy or Foodora are legally responsible for problems about the quality of the food, not the restaurants themselves.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://anwaltauskunft.de/magazin/leben/freizeit-alltag/1675/foodora-deliveroo-co-die-rechtslage-bei-den-neuen-lieferdiensten/|title=Foodora, Deliveroo & Co.: Die Rechtslage bei den neuen Lieferdiensten|series=Ern\u00e4hrung|publisher=Deutsche Anwaltauskunft (Das Rechtsportal des Deutschen Anwaltvereins)|date=6 May 2016|access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Economic impacts in the UK===\nIn December 2017, a study by macroeconomic consultancy Capital Economics revealed that Deliveroo has helped create 7,200 jobs across the restaurant sector since it launched in 2013, whilst also boosting the industry\u2019s revenue by \u00a3460 million in the year to June 2017. The report also found that Deliveroo helped add \u00a3372 million in value to the UK economy in the same 12-month period, a figure which Capital Economics projects to rise to \u00a31.5 billion in the year to June 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/12/19/nations-appetite-takeaway-could-make-deliveroo-worth-15bn-uk/|title=Nation's appetite for takeaway could make Deliveroo worth \u00a31.5bn to UK economy by 2019|first=Bradley|last=Gerrard|date=19 December 2017|publisher=Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Competition===\nDeliveroo's main competitors are [[Just Eat]], [[GrubHub]] and [[UberEATS]].<ref name=Telegraph />\n\nEarly June 2016, the German Hotel and Catering Association ({{lang-de|Deutscher Hotel- und Gastst\u00e4ttenverband}}) cautioned for delivery services such as Deliveroo or [[Foodora]] (a competitor using almost an identical business model; and at that time almost equally present in Germany), claiming that they attack their value chain without respect. In this warning, the Association wanted to prevent the market for food delivery services starting to resemble that of hotels, where businesses have become dependent on booking portals such as [[Booking.com]] or HRS but are unsatisfied with the commission fees charged by those portals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.zeit.de/wirtschaft/2016-06/foodora-lieferdienst-essen-geschaeftsmodell|title=Die pinkfarbene Verf\u00fchrung|newspaper=ZEIT ONLINE|date=7 June 2016|access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Just Eat]] announced that they were planning to compete with Deliveroo by moving into the restaurant chain market, working with local independent restaurants and chains.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/c57d9798-72a4-11e7-93ff-99f383b09ff9|title=Just Eat looks to battle Deliveroo for restaurant chains|newspaper=FT TIMES|date=27 July 2017|access-date=1 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Number of employees===\nOne media article reported that in early August 2016, Deliveroo had 800 employees,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-08-05/deliveroo-raises-275-million-to-escalate-food-delivery-wars |title=Deliveroo Raises $275 Million to Escalate Food-Delivery Wars |last=Satariano|first=Adam |website=Bloomberg.com|date=5 August 2016|access-date=9 August 2016}}</ref> while another article of around the same date reported there were 6,500 riders employed by the company.<ref name=\"Dubai\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/retail/food-delivery-service-deliveroo-aims-to-expand-in-dubai|title=Food delivery service Deliveroo aims to expand in Dubai|first=Sananda|last=Sahoo|date=7 August 2016|access-date=12 November 2016|newspaper=The National}}</ref> On 8 September 2016, ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported that 20,000 self-employed couriers were working for Deliveroo.<ref name=\"When-your-boss-is-an-algorithm\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/88fdc58e-754f-11e6-b60a-de4532d5ea35|title=When your boss is an algorithm|newspaper=The Financial Times|first=Sarah|last=O'Connor|date=8 September 2016|access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref> {{As of|2016|11}}, one source claimed that over 13,000 people worked at Deliveroo. In September 2017 Deliveroo confirmed that the company works with 30,000 riders across the globe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/09/21/deliveroo-revenues-grow-600pc-losses-stack/|title=Deliveroo revenues grow over 600pc but losses stack up|first=James|last=Titcomb|date=21 September 2017|publisher=Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Technical malfunctions ===\nOn 7 September 2016, the Deliveroo website and application crashed in the city of [[Chelmsford]], reportedly due to a high demand on the first night of launching its service in that city.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.essexlive.news/deliveroo-website-crashes-on-first-night-in-chelmsford/story-29692362-detail/story.html|title=Deliveroo website crashes on first night in Chelmsford|date=7 September 2016|access-date=13 November 2016|newspaper=EssexLive|first=Ric|last=Brown}}</ref>\n\nOn Tuesday 1 November 2016, at around 8PM (GMT) technical problems caused the Deliveroo system to be unable to operate for around an hour. Due to this malfunction, both its delivery applications, as well as its website went off-line. Reportedly, thousands of customers who had already paid for their orders got upset, also due to a lack of clear communication being provided by Deliveroo during the incident. Some customers had to wait for hours to get their food delivered.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/whats-on/food-drink-news/deliveroo-website-crashes-leaving-hungry-12114441|title=Deliveroo website crashes leaving hungry customers FUMING|date=1 November 2016|access-date=13 November 2016|newspaper=Birmingham Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/london-is-starving-hungry-londoners-left-angry-and-waiting-hours-for-food-after-deliveroo-site-a3384756.html|title='London is starving': Hungry Londoners left angry and waiting hours for food after Deliveroo site crashes|first=Francesca|last=Gillett|date=1 November 2016|access-date=13 November 2016|newspaper=EveningStandard}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bailiwickexpress.com/jsy/life/current-affairs/hungry-people-nation-go-state-panic-deliveroo-website-goes-down/|title=Hungry people of the nation go into a state of panic as Deliveroo website goes downHungry people of the nation go into a state of panic as Deliveroo website goes down|newspaper=Bailiwick Express|date=1 November 2016|access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/deliveroo-website-goes-down-leaving-9175888|title=Deliveroo website goes down leaving thousands of hungry customers waiting for their food|date=1 November 2016|first=Richard|last=Wheatstone|newspaper=Mirror Online}}</ref>\n\nDuring periods when the system is down, and therefore no deliveries are available for riders, Deliveroo pays riders a flat rate per hour until the system is restored.<ref>{{cite web |title=Guide to riding for Deliveroo and Uber Eats in the UK |url=https://yourconsumerguide.co.uk/2017/10/07/working-for-deliveroo-ubereats-uk/ |website=Your Consumer Guide |accessdate=16 May 2019 |date=7 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Funding ===\nIn June 2014, Deliveroo raised a \u00a32.75 million series A investment round from [[Index Ventures]] and Hoxton Ventures, as well as an assortment of [[angel investor]]s.<ref name=\"tech_Prem\">{{Cite web\n| title = Premium Restaurant Take-Out Platform Deliveroo Raises \u00a32.75M From Index ventures, Hoxton ventures, And Others\n| last = O'Hear | first = Steve\n| work = TechCrunch\n| date = \n| accessdate = 10 May 2016\n| url = https://techcrunch.com/2014/06/26/deliveroo/\n| quote = }}</ref> In January 2015, Roofoods Ltd, doing business as Deliveroo, received $25 million in series B funding led by [[Accel (venture capital firm)|Accel]] with participation from [[Index Ventures]], Hummingbird Ventures and Hoxton Ventures at an estimated valuation of $100 million.<ref name=WSJ>{{cite news|last1=Chapman|first1=Lizette|title=Food-Delivery Startup Deliveroo Picks Up $25 Million in Series B Funding|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2015/01/29/food-delivery-startup-deliveroo-picks-up-25-million-in-series-b-funding/|accessdate=18 September 2015|work=Daily Telegraph|date=29 January 2015}}</ref> At this time, Deliveroo was providing deliveries for approximately 750 restaurants. In July of that year, it secured a further $70 million in series C investment from [[Index Ventures]] and Greenoaks Capital, marking Deliveroo's third funding round in a year.\n\nIn November 2015, Deliveroo raised $100 million in Series D Funding.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|last1=Davidson|first1=Lauren|title=Deliveroo raises $100m|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/11/23/deliveroo-series-d|accessdate=23 November 2015|work=Tech Crunch|date=23 November 2015}}</ref> In August 2016, Deliveroo raised a Series E of $275 million from the hedge fund Bridgepoint.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/08/05/food-startup-deliveroo-raises-275m-as-uber-eats-into-its-european-market/|title=Food startup Deliveroo raises $275M as Uber eats into its European market|last=Lunden|first=Ingrid|last2=O'Hear|first2=Steve|website=TechCrunch|access-date=5 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the company announced a $385 million Series F round. An additional $98 million was announced in November, bringing the total round to $480 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/11/17/food-delivery-upstart-deliveroo-adds-another-98m-to-its-latest-round-now-at-480m/|title=Food delivery upstart Deliveroo adds $98M to its Series F, now totals $480M|last=Lunden|first=Ingrid|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-11-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, the company announced a $575 million Series G round led by Amazon, bringing the total round to $1.35 billion raised till date.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1e385cf6-7861-11e9-be7d-6d846537acab|title=Amazon leads $575m investment round in Deliveroo|last=Lunden|first=Ingrid|work=Financial times|access-date=2017-11-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Taylor Review ===\nIn October 2016 Prime Minister Theresa May announced a review into employment practices in the modern economy,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/employment-practices-in-the-modern-economy|title=Employment Practices in the Modern Economy|date=1 October 2016|publisher=HM Government|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref> chaired by Chief Executive of the RSA Matthew Taylor. The review was criticised as corrupt as it was revealed by the Financial Times that one of its members held shares in Deliveroo, a fact that was not disclosed to the public.<ref>'Taylor review member was early Deliveroo backer' (10 July 2017) [https://www.ft.com/content/95392a68-6596-11e7-8526-7b38dcaef614 Financial Times]</ref> In its submission<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.deliveroo.co.uk/news/taylor-review-submission.html|title=Deliveroo sets out plans to give greater protections to riders|date=7 July 2017|publisher=Deliveroo|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref> to the review, Deliveroo called on the Government to update legislation to allow the company to offer its riders rights - such as injury pay and sick pay - without limiting the flexibility which comes with self-employment. The company was the first in the on-demand economy to break ranks and ask for changes in legislation to enable it to offer self-employed riders more benefits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/deliveroo-breaks-ranks-by-offering-riders-sick-pay-l7z5rkzw3|title=Deliveroo breaks ranks by offering riders sick pay|first=Sam|last=Coates|date=7 July 2017|publisher=Times|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref> Deliveroo argued that current employment legislation means companies in the on-demand economy are forced to choose between offering riders flexible work and benefits. Deliveroo suggested that the Government either allow companies to offer entitlements to self-employed people or create a new category of employment in which benefits are calculated on the services they deliver instead of how many hours they work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/07/06/deliveroo-proposes-employment-laws-overhaul-let-give-riders/|title=Deliveroo proposes employment laws overhaul to let it give riders benefits|first=James|last=Titcomb|date=6 July 2017|publisher=Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Rider safety ===\nIn response to the attacks on moped drivers over the summer of 2017, Deliveroo announced a series of measures to help keep riders safe. Among the measures introduced were a new app feature that allows riders to raise security concerns, plus a trial of helmet cameras to allow Deliveroo to gather evidence and to pass on information to the police. The company also hired 50 new staff across the country who have a focus on rider safety.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40805224|title=Deliveroo takes steps to protect workers from violence|first=Catrin|last=Nye|date=3 August 2017|publisher=BBC|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/08/03/deliveroo-riders-wear-helmet-cameras-spate-acid-attacks/|title=Deliveroo riders to wear helmet cameras after spate of acid attacks|first=Cara|last=McGoogan|date=3 August 2017|publisher=Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Deliveroo announced that its riders will have access to the first ever insurance scheme for food delivery riders in the UK on-demand economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/insurance-offer-sweetens-gig-for-deliveroo-drivers-dv89ptgs3|title=Insurance offer sweetens gig for Deliveroo drivers|first=James|last=Hurley|date=6 December 2017|publisher=Times|access-date=28 January 2018}}</ref> As well as sickness and accident insurance cover, cyclists will also have access to the first-of-its-kind public liability insurance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business-reporter.co.uk/2017/12/06/deliveroo-riders-to-get-accident-and-illness-insurance-to-protect-income/|title=Deliveroo riders to get accident and illness insurance to protect income|date=6 December 2017|publisher=Business Reporter|access-date=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Leaving the German market ===\nOn 12 August 2019, Deliveroo sent an email to German customers stating their decision to leave the German market stating that all services will stop from 16 August.<ref>{{cite news |title=Food delivery service Deliveroo pulls out of Germany |url=https://www.dw.com/en/food-delivery-service-deliveroo-pulls-out-of-germany/a-49996572 |accessdate=13 August 2019 |agency=Deutsche Welle}}</ref> The email cited its inability to provide a sufficient quality of service and that it would focus on other markets. The announcement came days after acquiring Scottish startup Cultivate, and three months after raising \u00a3450 million in a funding round led by Amazon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.finance.yahoo.com/news/amazon-takes-bite-deliveroo-450-061951253.html|title=Amazon takes bite of Deliveroo in \u00a3450m funding round|website=uk.finance.yahoo.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Operations in Taiwan ===\nDeliveroo entered the Taiwan market in October 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shu |first1=Catherine |title=Deliveroo will enter Taiwan, its fourth market in the Asia-Pacific so far |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/09/11/deliveroo-will-enter-taiwan-its-fourth-market-in-the-asia-pacific-so-far/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=TechCrunch |date=11 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Boland |first1=Hannah |title=Deliveroo to launch in Taiwan as Asia push continues |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2018/09/12/deliveroo-launch-taiwan-asia-push-continues/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=12 September 2018}}</ref> In Taiwan, Deliveroo relied on contractors, according to an investigation by the [[Ministry of Labor (Taiwan)|Ministry of Labor]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shan |first1=Shelley |title=Most food drivers hired as staff: MOL |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/10/31/2003724973 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=31 October 2019}}</ref> As Deliveroo workers in Taiwan were not considered employees, it was unclear if the company were required to provide labor insurance to workers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Maxon |first1=Ann |title=MOL urged to protect couriers\u2019 rights |url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/10/16/2003724032 |work=Taipei Times |date=16 October 2019}}</ref> Despite not having the status of employees, Deliveroo and several courier services in Taiwan were cautioned by the labor ministry in 2019 that the {{ill|Occupational Safety and Health Act (Taiwan)|lt=Occupational Safety and Health Act|zh|\u8077\u696d\u5b89\u5168\u885b\u751f\u6cd5}} still applied to contractors. Therefore, Deliveroo agreed to suspend work for riders when the government suspends work for those with employee status due to natural disasters.<ref>{{cite news |title=Food delivery firms agree to typhoon day rules for drivers |url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/09/01/2003721501 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=1 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chang |first1=Hsiung-feng |last2=Chung |first2=Yu-chen |title=Food delivery services agree to use caution during typhoons |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/201908300017 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=31 August 2019}}</ref> In October 2019, Sharing Economy Association Taiwan proposed safety regulations that were agreed to by several courier services active in Taiwan, including Deliveroo.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shan |first1=Shelley |title=Association drafts rules to protect food couriers |url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/10/22/2003724408 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=22 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shan |first1=Shelley |title=Food-delivery platforms propose code of conduct |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/10/25/2003724606 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=25 October 2019}}</ref> That same month, Taiwan's [[Directorate General of Highways]] (DGH) fined Deliveroo for violations of the Highway Act, as it had not applied for a business license to establish an automobile transportation enterprise. Additionally, the DGH ordered Deliveroo to cease operations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Shu-fen |last2=Kao |first2=Evelyn |title=Food delivery companies ordered to cease operations |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/business/201910240003 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=24 October 2019}}</ref> Deliveroo announced its exit from Taiwan in April 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tsai |first1=Peng-min |last2=Lee |first2=Hsin-Yin |title=Food delivery company Deliveroo to cease operations in Taiwan |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/business/202004060019 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Deliveroo to exit Taiwan |url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/biz/archives/2020/04/08/2003734179 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Praise ==\nIn a 2016 study of the sharing economy, PwC wrote that 'the UK has also contributed one of the sharing economy's quickest-growing stars' in Deliveroo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwc.co.uk/issues/megatrends/collisions/sharingeconomy/outlook-for-the-sharing-economy-in-the-uk-2016.html|title=The sharing economy grows up: How the UK has embraced the sharing economy|publisher=PwC|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn awarding Deliveroo with 'Best Startup Founders' in the Europas Awards 2016, ''TechCrunch'' declared that founders Will Shu and Greg Orlowski 'have proved a rock-star team, scaling a high-growth business and introducing new thinking to the market.'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/06/17/the-europas-awards-2016-honored-the-best-tech-startups-in-europe/|title=The Europas Awards 2016 honored the best tech startups in Europe|first=Mike|last=Butcher|date=17 June 2016|publisher=TechCrunch|access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, ''Management Today'' argued that Deliveroo has become 'one of the best' in the food delivery sector 'thanks to its [[Unique selling proposition|USP]] of providing a network of dedicated couriers and an ordering platform, making it easy for restaurants which wouldn't otherwise offer delivery, to do so.'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.managementtoday.co.uk/real-innovation-awards-winners/future-business/article/1413951|title=Real Innovation Awards: The Winners|date=15 November 2016|publisher=Management Today|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nDeliveroo topped Deloitte's annual ranking of the UK's fastest growing technology companies in November 2017, with a four-year revenue growth of 107,117% - a record for the UK Technology Fast 50 awards. David Cobb, lead partner for the Deloitte UK Technology Fast 50 programme, commented: 'The achievements of this year's winner are truly remarkable: Deliveroo is now the fastest-growing technology company in the history of the competition. Their relentless growth has justifiably added them to the exclusive list of UK 'unicorns'. Everyone wants a slice of the online takeaway business, but very few have found success in the same way that Deliveroo has.'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.deloitte.com/uk/en/pages/press-releases/articles/records-break-as-deloitte-announces-the-2017-uk-technology-fast-50-winners.html|title=Records break as Deloitte announces the 2017 UK Technology Fast 50 winners|date=16 November 2017|publisher=Deloitte|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Criticisms ==\nAustralian-based employment lawyer [[Josh Bornstein]], principal at [[Maurice Blackburn (law firm)|Maurice Blackburn]], examined work contracts from Deliveroo and its competitor Foodora in late March 2016 and described the contracts as \"sham\", designed to pay workers \"below the award rates\" and to \"deny their basic benefits\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/workplace-relations/deliveroo-and-foodora-accused-of-using-sham-contacts-for-bicycle-delivery-riders-20160329-gnsu7g.html|title=Deliveroo and foodora accused of using sham contracts for bicycle delivery riders |first=Patrick|last=Hatch|date=30 March 2016|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nMaurice Blackburn announced that test cases against Deliveroo, as well as against Foodora, were being prepared wherein they were \"accused of under-paying their delivery riders and failing to meet minimum employment conditions\". Such allegations were confirmed by the Young Workers Centre in Australia, which claimed that the contracting arrangements by those companies left workers without access to [[minimum pay]] rates, [[Workers' compensation|WorkCover]] insurance, leave and [[superannuation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/workplace-relations/delivery-services-foodora-and-deliveroo-face-claims-of-exploitation-underpayment-20160728-gqfgwz.html|title=Delivery services Foodora and Deliveroo face claims of exploitation, underpayment|date=29 July 2016|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref> The Centre's \"Rights for Riders\" campaign aims \"to improve safety, pay, conditions and job security for food delivery riders\".<ref>Young Workers Centre, [http://www.youngworkers.org.au/rights4ridersfaq Rights for Riders FAQs], accessed 3 January 2017</ref>\n\nComplaints have also been made regarding the company's failure to provide cycle training and safety equipment (such as lights and [[Bicycle helmet|helmets]]) to its sometimes inexperienced riders. It has been argued that the need to race against the clock is another reason for risky cycling behaviour exhibited by the couriers; and that bikes should be checked for safety.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/deliveroo-cyclists-cause-road-mayhem-riding-against-the-clock-0m3l3rv0d|title=Deliveroo cyclists are accused of causing mayhem 'riding against the clock'|last2=Boswell|first2=Josh|date=5 June 2016|access-date=13 November 2016|first1=Grace|last1=Marsh|newspaper=The Sunday Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://road.cc/content/news/170695-deliveroo-criticised-letting-inexperienced-riders-loose-without-lights|title=Deliveroo criticised for letting inexperienced riders loose without lights|last=Laker|first=Laura|date=8 November 2016|website=road.cc|access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Strike ===\nDeliveroo's London drivers held a day-long strike in August 2016 to protest a new pay plan that they claimed would result in riders earning substantially below [[National Minimum Wage Act 1998|minimum wage]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/08/11/deliveroo-drivers-strike-in-row-over-pay-6060741/|title=Deliveroo drivers are on strike all day today in row over pay|first=Harry Readhead for|last=Metro.co.uk|date=11 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/aug/15/deliveroo-rider-after-an-accident-or-injury-we-are-on-our-own |title=Deliveroo rider: 'After an accident or injury we are on our own' - Business - The Guardian |date=15 August 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815110950/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/aug/15/deliveroo-rider-after-an-accident-or-injury-we-are-on-our-own |archivedate=15 August 2016 }}</ref> and the continuing lack of sick and accident pay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/why-deliveroo-strike-matters-future-workers-rights-1575773|title=Why the Deliveroo strike matters for the future of workers' rights|date=12 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian1\"/> The company later abandoned these plans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/deliveroo-strike-contract-minimum-wage-protest-plans-wont-be-forced-a7195291.html|title=Deliveroo has scrapped plans to force its 'absurd' new contract on staff|date=17 August 2016|language=en-GB|access-date=19 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring these strikes, as a means of protest, London Deliveroo drivers held up signs containing the [[neologism]] \"Slaveroo\", a term formed as a contraction between \"slavery\" and the company's name. The term and its corresponding social media [[hashtag]] were adopted by several news outlets, including non-English international media.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=International Business Times|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/london-deliveroo-drivers-stage-protest-over-slaveroo-changes-pay-1575603|title=London Deliveroo drivers stage protest over 'slaveroo' changes in pay|date=11 August 2016|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://novaramedia.com/2016/10/27/slaveroo-industrial-action-and-cooperativism-what-does-the-future-of-the-digital-platform-economy-hold/|title=#Slaveroo, Industrial Action and Cooperativism: What Does the Future of the Digital Platform Economy Hold?|first=Jim|last=Benfield|date=27 October 2016|access-date=12 November 2016|publisher=[[Novara Media]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberation.fr/futurs/2016/08/12/a-londres-les-coursiers-de-deliveroo-deja-en-greve_1471994|newspaper=Lib\u00e9ration|title=A Londres, les coursiers de Deliveroo d\u00e9j\u00e0 en gr\u00e8ve|first=Perinne|last=Signoret|date=12 August 2016|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vn.nl/waarom-het-succes-van-de-deliveroo-staking-een-beetje-hoop-geeft/|publisher=Vrij Nederland|title=Waarom het succes van de Deliveroo-staking een beetje hoop geeft|first=Clara|last=van de Wiel|date=17 August 2016|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of these protests, chair of the Independent Workers Union of Great Britain Couriers and Logistics Branch, which represents couriers and delivery drivers in London, Mags Dewhurst, published an article in ''The Guardian'' backing the protesters, saying that Deliveroo's claim of freedom and flexibility vis-\u00e0-vis its couriers are sham, calling it \"exploitation and exhaustion\" instead.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/aug/16/deliveroo-couriers-strike-freedom-william-shu|title=Deliveroo couriers are right to strike: the company's claims of freedom are a sham|first=Mags|last=Dewhurst|date=16 August 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 November 2016, news headlines covered the demand of a small group of UK Deliveroo drivers to seek union recognition by the company. The Independent Workers Union of Great Britain (IWGB) represented the drivers in the [[Camden Town|Camden]] area of [[north London]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-britain-deliveroo-idUKKBN1331A7|title=After Uber case, UK union pushes for pay deal at Deliveroo|series=Technology News|date=8 November 2016|access-date=13 November 2016|publisher=REUTERS|first=Costas|last=Pitas|editor-first=Stephen|editor-last=Addison}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/deliveroo-union-minimum-wage-uber-workers-rights-ruling-a7404326.html|title=Deliveroo drivers demand union recognition and minimum wage after Uber workers' rights ruling|first=Ben|last=Chapman|date=8 November 2016|access-date=13 November 2016|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/32308032-a599-11e6-8898-79a99e2a4de6|title=Deliveroo couriers demand union recognition and rights in UK|series=Gig Economy|first=Madhumita|last=Murgia|date=8 November 2016|newspaper=The Financial Times|access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-37905425|title=Deliveroo riders seek to unionise and gain workers' rights|first=Clive|last=Coleman|newspaper=BBC News|date=8 November 2016|access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref> In November 2017, the Central Arbitration Committee dismissed the challenge by the IWGB and ruled that Deliveroo riders are self-employed. Deliveroo welcomed the decision as a 'victory for riders [who] value the flexibility that self-employment provides'.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/11/14/deliveroo-wins-landmark-legal-victory-riders-working-rights/|title=Deliveroo wins landmark legal victory against union claim|first=James|last=Titcomb|date=14 November 2017|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-November 2016, it was reported that Deliveroo's CEO, Will Shu, almost doubled his salary around the same time that low-paid Deliveroo drivers were demanding better employment conditions. Shu increased his pay to \u00a3102,135 in the year to December 2015, from \u00a353,333 the year before that.<ref name=\"Fury-as-Deliveroo-boss-nearly-doubles-his-pay-while-his-workers-fight\" />\n\nIn May 2017, Deliveroo workers protested working conditions in Berlin, Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.de/20170518/foodora-and-deliveroo-couriers-protest-working-conditions-in-berlin|title=Foodora and Deliveroo couriers protest working conditions in Berlin|date=18 May 2017|language=en-GB|access-date=1 March 2018}}</ref> In January 2018, Deliveroo riders went on strike in Belgium and in the Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/01/20/deliveroo-riders-go-strike-belgium-netherlands/|title=Deliveroo riders go on strike in Belgium and Netherlands|date=20 January 2018|language=en-GB|access-date=1 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===The Netherlands===\nIn 2017 and 2018 Dutch online consumer affairs journalist Tim Hofman investigated Deliveroo undercover, asserting that the company forced its delivery staff to declare themselves self-employed rather than being employees of the company, which would give them rights to benefits such as sick pay. The investigation and presentation of the evidence to Deliveroo management were released as episodes of the #BOOS online programme.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bogosavac |first1=Nina |title=Deliveroo nog meer onder druk na nieuwe undercover #Boos-aflevering |url=http://vance.nl/deliveroo-nog-meer-onder-druk-na-nieuwe-undercover-boos-aflevering/ |website=Vance |publisher=OKGO BV |accessdate=5 December 2019 |language=NL |date=23 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===London===\nIn London from 2019, it has been widely reported and confirmed that Deliveroo are paying its riders progressively less per delivery whilst pushing the pickup/delivery distances further for the lower fee.  It has been noted this practice in particular penalises scooter riders, who frequently find themselves being required to travel 1-2+ miles to perform a pickup, only to then undertake a delivery 3\u20134 miles away (totalling 5-6+), with no material visible distance benefit being paid over the base fee. The riders subsequently find themselves significantly 'out of zone', potentially in an area with low coverage, 'marooned', and no longer receiving orders unless they make the journey back in to zone first. This results in significant time wastage for the rider, undermining their ability to earn a reasonable hourly wage.\n\nAnother undermining tactic that has been observed is where riders, who might even have an excellent to exemplary 'performance statistic', arbitrarily have their previously reserved 'repeat' hours cut without warning, sometimes drastically (a cut of 4-plus days of work in a single week has been observed), from their pre-booking weekly calendar for no justifiable reason, thus seriously affecting the rider's ability to earn a stable income.  The reason given by Deliveroo was that the hours were given to other riders to meet the (over-subscribed) demand. This behaviour could potentially be interpreted as discriminatory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gigebyte.com/deliveroo-cuts-rider-fees-to-cover-longer-distances|title=Deliveroo cuts rider fees whilst at the same time covering longer distances|date=10 April 2019|language=en-GB|access-date=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*E McGaughey, 'Uber, the Taylor Review, and the duty to not misrepresent employment status' (2018) [https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3018516 Industrial Law Journal]\n*E McGaughey, 'Taylorooism: When Network Technology Meets Corporate Power' (2018) [https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3247605 Industrial Relations Journal]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Deliveroo}}\n*{{Official website|deliveroo.co.uk}}\n{{Online food ordering}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deliveroo}}\n[[Category:British companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Online companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Online food ordering]]\n[[Category:Companies based in the City of Westminster]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Food delivery company}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Roofoods Ltd.\n| logo = Deliveroo logo.svg\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| trade_name = Deliveroo\n| industry = {{Unbulleted list|[[Online food ordering]]|[[Food delivery]]}}\n| founder = [[Will Shu]]\n| hq_location = London, England, UK\n| area_served = {{Unbulleted list|[[United Kingdom]]|[[Netherlands]]|[[France]]|[[Belgium]]|[[Hong Kong]]|[[Ireland]]|[[Spain]]|[[Italy]]|[[Australia]]|[[Singapore]]|[[Kuwait]]|[[Puerto Rico]]|[[United Arab Emirates]]}}\n| key_people = Will Shu ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]]) <br> Greg Orlowski <br> Dan Winn ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]]) <br> Rohan Pradhan ([[Chief operating officer|COO]])\n| products = \n| revenue = \u00a3277.1 M (2017) <ref>{{Citation|title=Deliveroo profile |work=Craft |url=https://craft.co/deliveroo|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n| num_employees = 5,699 (2019)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://craft.co/deliveroo|title=Deliveroo Company Profile |publisher=Craft|accessdate=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n* Around 20,000 technically self-employed couriers ({{As of|2016|9|lc=y}})<ref name=\"When-your-boss-is-an-algorithm\" />\n| website = {{url|deliveroo.co.uk}}\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2013}}\n}}\n\n'''Roofoods Ltd.''' (branded as '''Deliveroo''') is an online [[food delivery]] company founded in 2013 by [[Will Shu]] and Greg Orlowski.<ref name=Deliverooleaflet /> Based in [[London]], England, it operates in two hundred cities<ref name=Sassard2017 /> in the United Kingdom, the Netherlands, France, Belgium, Ireland, Spain, Italy, Australia, Singapore, United Arab Emirates, Hong Kong, and Kuwait. A subsidiary operation, '''Deliveroo Editions''', focuses on developing a network of [[ghost kitchen]]s\u2014kitchens located off-site from restaurants for the preparation of delivery-only meals.<ref name=\"Sawera, VB, Deliveroo, 4/5/2017\">{{cite web |last1=Sawers |first1=Paul |title=Food courier Deliveroo launches platform for restaurants to open delivery-only kitchens |url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/04/05/food-courier-deliveroo-launches-platform-for-restaurants-to-open-delivery-only-kitchens/ |website=VentureBeat.com |accessdate=17 June 2019 |date=April 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Business==\n===History and basic operations===\nThe company Deliveroo, headquartered in London, was founded in 2013 by Will Shu and Greg Orlowski, both Americans.<ref name=Deliverooleaflet>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/information_society/newsroom/image/document/2016-6/deliveroo_13855.pdf|title=Introduction to Deliveroo|date=4 February 2016|access-date=12 November 2016|website=European Commission|author=Deliveroo}}</ref> The company makes money by charging restaurants a commission fee, as well as by charging customers a fee per order.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/parmyolson/2016/02/17/deliveroo-army-5000-drivers-3-years/|title=Here's How Deliveroo Built An Army Of 5,000 Drivers In Just 3 Years|first=Parmy|last=Olson|work=Forbes|date=17 February 2016|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref> It operates in two hundred cities<ref name=Sassard2017>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/deliveroo-fundraising/uks-deliveroo-raises-nearly-500-mln-ahead-of-200th-city-launch-idUSL8N1NN4JE|title=UK's Deliveroo raises nearly $500 mln ahead of 200th city launch |first=Sophie|last=Sassard |date=17 November 2017 |publisher=Reuters|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref> in the [[UK]], and in the [[Netherlands]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Belgium]], [[Ireland]], [[Spain]], [[Italy]], [[Australia]], [[Singapore]], [[United Arab Emirates]], [[Kuwait]] and [[Hong Kong]].\n\nOrders are placed through its app or website and then [[self-employed]]<ref name=Beeger2016>{{cite news |url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/wirtschaft/menschen-wirtschaft/vor-und-nachteile-der-gig-economy-14357206.html|title=Die Chancen der \"Gig-Economy\". Digitalisierter Arbeitsmarkt |trans-title=The Chances of the Gig Economy, digitized labour market |date=26 July 2016|access-date=14 November 2016|first=Britta|last=Beeger|newspaper=Frankfurter Allgemeine |language=German |quote=Und auch der Essenslieferdienst Deliveroo, der derzeit Fahrer mit gro\u00dfen Thermo-Rucks\u00e4cken durch die Gro\u00dfst\u00e4dte schickt, sucht seinen Stellenausschreibungen zufolge Fahrer, die selbst\u00e4ndig oder auf Midijobbasis t\u00e4tig sind. English: And the delivery service Deliveroo, which currently sends drivers with large thermo-backpacks through the cities, looking for job advertisements according to drivers who operate independently or on a Midi-job basis.}}</ref> [[Bicycle courier|bicycle]] or [[motorcycle courier|motorcycle]] couriers transport orders from restaurants to customers.\n\nIn November 2017 Deliveroo introduced Deliveroo Plus, a subscription service which gives customers in the UK unlimited free delivery<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/deliveroos-subscription-service-is-now-available-across-the-uk-2017-11?r=US&IR=T|title=Deliveroo's \u00a37.99 a month subscription service is now available across the UK|first=Sam|last=Shead|date=8 November 2017|publisher=BusinessInsider|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nDeliveroo works with some of the biggest chain restaurants across the UK, with the majority being available exclusively on the Deliveroo app along with thousands of independent restaurants.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deliveroo.co.uk/sitemap/|title=Deliveroo Sitemap|publisher=Deliveroo|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.deliveroo.co.uk/news/death-of-the-lunchbox.html|title=Death of the Lunchbox?|date=24 April 2017|publisher=Deliveroo|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref> On 16 November 2016, it became known that the brewing company [[Heineken International]] had closed a deal for Deliveroo to deliver the latter's beers and ciders, initially across 15 sites in London, Bath and Cardiff. This delivery deal, whose activities started that same week, was considered the biggest one of its kind (that is, with regards to the brewing industry). Further expansion of these activities across the UK were planned by the end of the year 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/11/16/heineken-joins-deliveroo-to-create-booze-delivery-brand/|title=Heineken joins Deliveroo to create booze delivery brand|series=Business|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=16 November 2016|access-date=18 November 2016|first=Jillian|last=Ambrose}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.beveragedaily.com/Retail-Shopper-Insights/Deliveroo-Heineken-partner-on-beer-delivery-brand|title=Deliveroo and Heineken partner to launch beer delivery brand|newspaper=Beverage Daily|first=Rachel|last=Arthur|date=17 November 2016|access-date=18 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Deliveroo announced plans to create 300 UK tech jobs when it opens its new head office in London later in 2017. Also in January 2017, the British-born company employed more than 1,000 full-time staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-38659329|title=Deliveroo to add 300 UK tech jobs in new London office|work=BBC News|date=18 January 2017|access-date=18 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nDeliveroo\u2019s Editions kitchens launched in April 2017. These delivery-only kitchens, sometimes known as [[ghost restaurant]]s, allow restaurants to access customers in locations without needing [[High Street]] premises, thereby reducing set-up costs compared to a full-service restaurant. Deliveroo uses its data to identify areas where customer demand for certain cuisines is high and predicts which restaurants are likely to succeed there.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/04/05/deliveroo-opens-30-kitchens-meet-surging-takeaway-demand/|title=Deliveroo opens 30 kitchens to meet surging takeaway demand|first=James|last=Titcomb|date=5 April 2017|publisher=Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1e516472-1a11-11e7-a266-12672483791a|title=Deliveroo expands with standalone takeaway kitchens|first=Madhumita|last=Murgia|date=5 April 2017|publisher=Financial Times|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-June 2016, the founders of Deliveroo, Will Shu and Greg Orlowski received an award for the \"Best Startup Founders\" as part of \"The Europas Startup Conference and Awards\", which are given to [[Technology company|technology companies]]. The company also received Fastest Rising Startup of the Year and the Europas Grand Prix award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/06/17/the-europas-awards-2016-honored-the-best-tech-startups-in-europe/|title=The Europas Awards 2016 honored the best tech startups in Europe|first=Mike|last=Butcher|date=17 June 2016|publisher=TechCrunch|access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nDeliveroo recorded a loss of \u00a31.4m for the year 2015. Mid-November 2016, the company reported a loss of \u00a318.1 million for that year. In September 2017 Deliveroo recorded a growth in global revenue of 611% in 2016, with sales of \u00a3128.6 million, while \"losses soared from \u00a330.1m to \u00a3129.1m\".<ref name=\"Deliveroo-boss-doubled-his-pau-ahead-of-riders\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/nov/11/deliveroo-boss-pay-ahead-riders-protest|title=Deliveroo boss doubled his pay ahead of riders' protest |newspaper=The Guardian|date=11 November 2016|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Fury-as-Deliveroo-boss-nearly-doubles-his-pay-while-his-workers-fight\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/markets/article-3928578/Fury-Deliveroo-boss-nearly-doubles-pay-workers-fight-better-wages.html |title=Fury as Deliveroo boss nearly doubles his pay while his workers fight for better wages|date=11 November 2016|access-date=12 November 2016|newspaper=This is MONEY}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/09/21/deliveroo-revenues-grow-600pc-losses-stack/|title=Deliveroo revenues grow over 600pc but losses stack up |first=James|last=Titcomb|date=21 September 2017|publisher=Daily Telegraph |access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Deliveroo Rider Taking The Lane In Bristol (32611782273).jpg|thumb|Deliveroo cyclist in the UK]]\nDeliveroo provides the delivery service as well as [[marketing]] and order taking, allowing it to provide food from restaurants that do not normally offer a delivery service. In a press release of May 2016, the German Bar Association ({{lang-de|Der Deutsche Anwaltverein}}) informed the public that delivery companies such as Deliveroo, Take Eat Easy or Foodora are legally responsible for problems about the quality of the food, not the restaurants themselves.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://anwaltauskunft.de/magazin/leben/freizeit-alltag/1675/foodora-deliveroo-co-die-rechtslage-bei-den-neuen-lieferdiensten/|title=Foodora, Deliveroo & Co.: Die Rechtslage bei den neuen Lieferdiensten|series=Ern\u00e4hrung|publisher=Deutsche Anwaltauskunft (Das Rechtsportal des Deutschen Anwaltvereins)|date=6 May 2016|access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Economic impacts in the UK===\nIn December 2017, a study by macroeconomic consultancy Capital Economics revealed that Deliveroo has helped create 7,200 jobs across the restaurant sector since it launched in 2013, whilst also boosting the industry\u2019s revenue by \u00a3460 million in the year to June 2017. The report also found that Deliveroo helped add \u00a3372 million in value to the UK economy in the same 12-month period, a figure which Capital Economics projects to rise to \u00a31.5 billion in the year to June 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/12/19/nations-appetite-takeaway-could-make-deliveroo-worth-15bn-uk/|title=Nation's appetite for takeaway could make Deliveroo worth \u00a31.5bn to UK economy by 2019|first=Bradley|last=Gerrard|date=19 December 2017|publisher=Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Competition===\nDeliveroo's main competitors are [[Just Eat]], [[GrubHub]] and [[UberEATS]].<ref name=Telegraph />\n\nEarly June 2016, the German Hotel and Catering Association ({{lang-de|Deutscher Hotel- und Gastst\u00e4ttenverband}}) cautioned for delivery services such as Deliveroo or [[Foodora]] (a competitor using almost an identical business model; and at that time almost equally present in Germany), claiming that they attack their value chain without respect. In this warning, the Association wanted to prevent the market for food delivery services starting to resemble that of hotels, where businesses have become dependent on booking portals such as [[Booking.com]] or HRS but are unsatisfied with the commission fees charged by those portals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.zeit.de/wirtschaft/2016-06/foodora-lieferdienst-essen-geschaeftsmodell|title=Die pinkfarbene Verf\u00fchrung|newspaper=ZEIT ONLINE|date=7 June 2016|access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Just Eat]] announced that they were planning to compete with Deliveroo by moving into the restaurant chain market, working with local independent restaurants and chains.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/c57d9798-72a4-11e7-93ff-99f383b09ff9|title=Just Eat looks to battle Deliveroo for restaurant chains|newspaper=FT TIMES|date=27 July 2017|access-date=1 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Number of employees===\nOne media article reported that in early August 2016, Deliveroo had 800 employees,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-08-05/deliveroo-raises-275-million-to-escalate-food-delivery-wars |title=Deliveroo Raises $275 Million to Escalate Food-Delivery Wars |last=Satariano|first=Adam |website=Bloomberg.com|date=5 August 2016|access-date=9 August 2016}}</ref> while another article of around the same date reported there were 6,500 riders employed by the company.<ref name=\"Dubai\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/retail/food-delivery-service-deliveroo-aims-to-expand-in-dubai|title=Food delivery service Deliveroo aims to expand in Dubai|first=Sananda|last=Sahoo|date=7 August 2016|access-date=12 November 2016|newspaper=The National}}</ref> On 8 September 2016, ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported that 20,000 self-employed couriers were working for Deliveroo.<ref name=\"When-your-boss-is-an-algorithm\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/88fdc58e-754f-11e6-b60a-de4532d5ea35|title=When your boss is an algorithm|newspaper=The Financial Times|first=Sarah|last=O'Connor|date=8 September 2016|access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref> {{As of|2016|11}}, one source claimed that over 13,000 people worked at Deliveroo. In September 2017 Deliveroo confirmed that the company works with 30,000 riders across the globe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/09/21/deliveroo-revenues-grow-600pc-losses-stack/|title=Deliveroo revenues grow over 600pc but losses stack up|first=James|last=Titcomb|date=21 September 2017|publisher=Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Technical malfunctions ===\nOn 7 September 2016, the Deliveroo website and application crashed in the city of [[Chelmsford]], reportedly due to a high demand on the first night of launching its service in that city.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.essexlive.news/deliveroo-website-crashes-on-first-night-in-chelmsford/story-29692362-detail/story.html|title=Deliveroo website crashes on first night in Chelmsford|date=7 September 2016|access-date=13 November 2016|newspaper=EssexLive|first=Ric|last=Brown}}</ref>\n\nOn Tuesday 1 November 2016, at around 8PM (GMT) technical problems caused the Deliveroo system to be unable to operate for around an hour. Due to this malfunction, both its delivery applications, as well as its website went off-line. Reportedly, thousands of customers who had already paid for their orders got upset, also due to a lack of clear communication being provided by Deliveroo during the incident. Some customers had to wait for hours to get their food delivered.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/whats-on/food-drink-news/deliveroo-website-crashes-leaving-hungry-12114441|title=Deliveroo website crashes leaving hungry customers FUMING|date=1 November 2016|access-date=13 November 2016|newspaper=Birmingham Mail}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/london-is-starving-hungry-londoners-left-angry-and-waiting-hours-for-food-after-deliveroo-site-a3384756.html|title='London is starving': Hungry Londoners left angry and waiting hours for food after Deliveroo site crashes|first=Francesca|last=Gillett|date=1 November 2016|access-date=13 November 2016|newspaper=EveningStandard}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bailiwickexpress.com/jsy/life/current-affairs/hungry-people-nation-go-state-panic-deliveroo-website-goes-down/|title=Hungry people of the nation go into a state of panic as Deliveroo website goes downHungry people of the nation go into a state of panic as Deliveroo website goes down|newspaper=Bailiwick Express|date=1 November 2016|access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/deliveroo-website-goes-down-leaving-9175888|title=Deliveroo website goes down leaving thousands of hungry customers waiting for their food|date=1 November 2016|first=Richard|last=Wheatstone|newspaper=Mirror Online}}</ref>\n\nDuring periods when the system is down, and therefore no deliveries are available for riders, Deliveroo pays riders a flat rate per hour until the system is restored.<ref>{{cite web |title=Guide to riding for Deliveroo and Uber Eats in the UK |url=https://yourconsumerguide.co.uk/2017/10/07/working-for-deliveroo-ubereats-uk/ |website=Your Consumer Guide |accessdate=16 May 2019 |date=7 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Funding ===\nIn June 2014, Deliveroo raised a \u00a32.75 million series A investment round from [[Index Ventures]] and Hoxton Ventures, as well as an assortment of [[angel investor]]s.<ref name=\"tech_Prem\">{{Cite web\n| title = Premium Restaurant Take-Out Platform Deliveroo Raises \u00a32.75M From Index ventures, Hoxton ventures, And Others\n| last = O'Hear | first = Steve\n| work = TechCrunch\n| date = \n| accessdate = 10 May 2016\n| url = https://techcrunch.com/2014/06/26/deliveroo/\n| quote = }}</ref> In January 2015, Roofoods Ltd, doing business as Deliveroo, received $25 million in series B funding led by [[Accel (venture capital firm)|Accel]] with participation from [[Index Ventures]], Hummingbird Ventures and Hoxton Ventures at an estimated valuation of $100 million.<ref name=WSJ>{{cite news|last1=Chapman|first1=Lizette|title=Food-Delivery Startup Deliveroo Picks Up $25 Million in Series B Funding|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2015/01/29/food-delivery-startup-deliveroo-picks-up-25-million-in-series-b-funding/|accessdate=18 September 2015|work=Daily Telegraph|date=29 January 2015}}</ref> At this time, Deliveroo was providing deliveries for approximately 750 restaurants. In July of that year, it secured a further $70 million in series C investment from [[Index Ventures]] and Greenoaks Capital, marking Deliveroo's third funding round in a year.\n\nIn November 2015, Deliveroo raised $100 million in Series D Funding.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|last1=Davidson|first1=Lauren|title=Deliveroo raises $100m|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/11/23/deliveroo-series-d|accessdate=23 November 2015|work=Tech Crunch|date=23 November 2015}}</ref> In August 2016, Deliveroo raised a Series E of $275 million from the hedge fund Bridgepoint.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/08/05/food-startup-deliveroo-raises-275m-as-uber-eats-into-its-european-market/|title=Food startup Deliveroo raises $275M as Uber eats into its European market|last=Lunden|first=Ingrid|last2=O'Hear|first2=Steve|website=TechCrunch|access-date=5 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the company announced a $385 million Series F round. An additional $98 million was announced in November, bringing the total round to $480 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/11/17/food-delivery-upstart-deliveroo-adds-another-98m-to-its-latest-round-now-at-480m/|title=Food delivery upstart Deliveroo adds $98M to its Series F, now totals $480M|last=Lunden|first=Ingrid|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-11-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, the company announced a $575 million Series G round led by Amazon, bringing the total round to $1.35 billion raised till date.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1e385cf6-7861-11e9-be7d-6d846537acab|title=Amazon leads $575m investment round in Deliveroo|last=Lunden|first=Ingrid|work=Financial times|access-date=2017-11-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Taylor Review ===\nIn October 2016 Prime Minister Theresa May announced a review into employment practices in the modern economy,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/employment-practices-in-the-modern-economy|title=Employment Practices in the Modern Economy|date=1 October 2016|publisher=HM Government|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref> chaired by Chief Executive of the RSA Matthew Taylor. The review was criticised as corrupt as it was revealed by the Financial Times that one of its members held shares in Deliveroo, a fact that was not disclosed to the public.<ref>'Taylor review member was early Deliveroo backer' (10 July 2017) [https://www.ft.com/content/95392a68-6596-11e7-8526-7b38dcaef614 Financial Times]</ref> In its submission<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.deliveroo.co.uk/news/taylor-review-submission.html|title=Deliveroo sets out plans to give greater protections to riders|date=7 July 2017|publisher=Deliveroo|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref> to the review, Deliveroo called on the Government to update legislation to allow the company to offer its riders rights - such as injury pay and sick pay - without limiting the flexibility which comes with self-employment. The company was the first in the on-demand economy to break ranks and ask for changes in legislation to enable it to offer self-employed riders more benefits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/deliveroo-breaks-ranks-by-offering-riders-sick-pay-l7z5rkzw3|title=Deliveroo breaks ranks by offering riders sick pay|first=Sam|last=Coates|date=7 July 2017|publisher=Times|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref> Deliveroo argued that current employment legislation means companies in the on-demand economy are forced to choose between offering riders flexible work and benefits. Deliveroo suggested that the Government either allow companies to offer entitlements to self-employed people or create a new category of employment in which benefits are calculated on the services they deliver instead of how many hours they work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/07/06/deliveroo-proposes-employment-laws-overhaul-let-give-riders/|title=Deliveroo proposes employment laws overhaul to let it give riders benefits|first=James|last=Titcomb|date=6 July 2017|publisher=Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Rider safety ===\nIn response to the attacks on moped drivers over the summer of 2017, Deliveroo announced a series of measures to help keep riders safe. Among the measures introduced were a new app feature that allows riders to raise security concerns, plus a trial of helmet cameras to allow Deliveroo to gather evidence and to pass on information to the police. The company also hired 50 new staff across the country who have a focus on rider safety.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40805224|title=Deliveroo takes steps to protect workers from violence|first=Catrin|last=Nye|date=3 August 2017|publisher=BBC|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/08/03/deliveroo-riders-wear-helmet-cameras-spate-acid-attacks/|title=Deliveroo riders to wear helmet cameras after spate of acid attacks|first=Cara|last=McGoogan|date=3 August 2017|publisher=Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Deliveroo announced that its riders will have access to the first ever insurance scheme for food delivery riders in the UK on-demand economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/insurance-offer-sweetens-gig-for-deliveroo-drivers-dv89ptgs3|title=Insurance offer sweetens gig for Deliveroo drivers|first=James|last=Hurley|date=6 December 2017|publisher=Times|access-date=28 January 2018}}</ref> As well as sickness and accident insurance cover, cyclists will also have access to the first-of-its-kind public liability insurance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business-reporter.co.uk/2017/12/06/deliveroo-riders-to-get-accident-and-illness-insurance-to-protect-income/|title=Deliveroo riders to get accident and illness insurance to protect income|date=6 December 2017|publisher=Business Reporter|access-date=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Leaving the German market ===\nOn 12 August 2019, Deliveroo sent an email to German customers stating their decision to leave the German market stating that all services will stop from 16 August.<ref>{{cite news |title=Food delivery service Deliveroo pulls out of Germany |url=https://www.dw.com/en/food-delivery-service-deliveroo-pulls-out-of-germany/a-49996572 |accessdate=13 August 2019 |agency=Deutsche Welle}}</ref> The email cited its inability to provide a sufficient quality of service and that it would focus on other markets. The announcement came days after acquiring Scottish startup Cultivate, and three months after raising \u00a3450 million in a funding round led by Amazon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.finance.yahoo.com/news/amazon-takes-bite-deliveroo-450-061951253.html|title=Amazon takes bite of Deliveroo in \u00a3450m funding round|website=uk.finance.yahoo.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Operations in Taiwan ===\nDeliveroo entered the Taiwan market in October 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shu |first1=Catherine |title=Deliveroo will enter Taiwan, its fourth market in the Asia-Pacific so far |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/09/11/deliveroo-will-enter-taiwan-its-fourth-market-in-the-asia-pacific-so-far/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=TechCrunch |date=11 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Boland |first1=Hannah |title=Deliveroo to launch in Taiwan as Asia push continues |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2018/09/12/deliveroo-launch-taiwan-asia-push-continues/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=12 September 2018}}</ref> In Taiwan, Deliveroo relied on contractors, according to an investigation by the [[Ministry of Labor (Taiwan)|Ministry of Labor]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shan |first1=Shelley |title=Most food drivers hired as staff: MOL |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/10/31/2003724973 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=31 October 2019}}</ref> As Deliveroo workers in Taiwan were not considered employees, it was unclear if the company were required to provide labor insurance to workers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Maxon |first1=Ann |title=MOL urged to protect couriers\u2019 rights |url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/10/16/2003724032 |work=Taipei Times |date=16 October 2019}}</ref> Despite not having the status of employees, Deliveroo and several courier services in Taiwan were cautioned by the labor ministry in 2019 that the {{ill|Occupational Safety and Health Act (Taiwan)|lt=Occupational Safety and Health Act|zh|\u8077\u696d\u5b89\u5168\u885b\u751f\u6cd5}} still applied to contractors. Therefore, Deliveroo agreed to suspend work for riders when the government suspends work for those with employee status due to natural disasters.<ref>{{cite news |title=Food delivery firms agree to typhoon day rules for drivers |url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/09/01/2003721501 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=1 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chang |first1=Hsiung-feng |last2=Chung |first2=Yu-chen |title=Food delivery services agree to use caution during typhoons |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/201908300017 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=31 August 2019}}</ref> In October 2019, Sharing Economy Association Taiwan proposed safety regulations that were agreed to by several courier services active in Taiwan, including Deliveroo.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shan |first1=Shelley |title=Association drafts rules to protect food couriers |url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/10/22/2003724408 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=22 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shan |first1=Shelley |title=Food-delivery platforms propose code of conduct |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/10/25/2003724606 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=25 October 2019}}</ref> That same month, Taiwan's [[Directorate General of Highways]] (DGH) fined Deliveroo for violations of the Highway Act, as it had not applied for a business license to establish an automobile transportation enterprise. Additionally, the DGH ordered Deliveroo to cease operations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Shu-fen |last2=Kao |first2=Evelyn |title=Food delivery companies ordered to cease operations |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/business/201910240003 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=24 October 2019}}</ref> Deliveroo announced its exit from Taiwan in April 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tsai |first1=Peng-min |last2=Lee |first2=Hsin-Yin |title=Food delivery company Deliveroo to cease operations in Taiwan |url=https://focustaiwan.tw/business/202004060019 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |agency=Central News Agency |date=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Deliveroo to exit Taiwan |url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/biz/archives/2020/04/08/2003734179 |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Taipei Times |date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Praise ==\nIn a 2016 study of the sharing economy, PwC wrote that 'the UK has also contributed one of the sharing economy's quickest-growing stars' in Deliveroo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwc.co.uk/issues/megatrends/collisions/sharingeconomy/outlook-for-the-sharing-economy-in-the-uk-2016.html|title=The sharing economy grows up: How the UK has embraced the sharing economy|publisher=PwC|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn awarding Deliveroo with 'Best Startup Founders' in the Europas Awards 2016, ''TechCrunch'' declared that founders Will Shu and Greg Orlowski 'have proved a rock-star team, scaling a high-growth business and introducing new thinking to the market.'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/06/17/the-europas-awards-2016-honored-the-best-tech-startups-in-europe/|title=The Europas Awards 2016 honored the best tech startups in Europe|first=Mike|last=Butcher|date=17 June 2016|publisher=TechCrunch|access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, ''Management Today'' argued that Deliveroo has become 'one of the best' in the food delivery sector 'thanks to its [[Unique selling proposition|USP]] of providing a network of dedicated couriers and an ordering platform, making it easy for restaurants which wouldn't otherwise offer delivery, to do so.'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.managementtoday.co.uk/real-innovation-awards-winners/future-business/article/1413951|title=Real Innovation Awards: The Winners|date=15 November 2016|publisher=Management Today|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nDeliveroo topped Deloitte's annual ranking of the UK's fastest growing technology companies in November 2017, with a four-year revenue growth of 107,117% - a record for the UK Technology Fast 50 awards. David Cobb, lead partner for the Deloitte UK Technology Fast 50 programme, commented: 'The achievements of this year's winner are truly remarkable: Deliveroo is now the fastest-growing technology company in the history of the competition. Their relentless growth has justifiably added them to the exclusive list of UK 'unicorns'. Everyone wants a slice of the online takeaway business, but very few have found success in the same way that Deliveroo has.'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.deloitte.com/uk/en/pages/press-releases/articles/records-break-as-deloitte-announces-the-2017-uk-technology-fast-50-winners.html|title=Records break as Deloitte announces the 2017 UK Technology Fast 50 winners|date=16 November 2017|publisher=Deloitte|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Criticisms ==\nAustralian-based employment lawyer [[Josh Bornstein]], principal at [[Maurice Blackburn (law firm)|Maurice Blackburn]], examined work contracts from Deliveroo and its competitor Foodora in late March 2016 and described the contracts as \"sham\", designed to pay workers \"below the award rates\" and to \"deny their basic benefits\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/workplace-relations/deliveroo-and-foodora-accused-of-using-sham-contacts-for-bicycle-delivery-riders-20160329-gnsu7g.html|title=Deliveroo and foodora accused of using sham contracts for bicycle delivery riders |first=Patrick|last=Hatch|date=30 March 2016|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nMaurice Blackburn announced that test cases against Deliveroo, as well as against Foodora, were being prepared wherein they were \"accused of under-paying their delivery riders and failing to meet minimum employment conditions\". Such allegations were confirmed by the Young Workers Centre in Australia, which claimed that the contracting arrangements by those companies left workers without access to [[minimum pay]] rates, [[Workers' compensation|WorkCover]] insurance, leave and [[superannuation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/workplace-relations/delivery-services-foodora-and-deliveroo-face-claims-of-exploitation-underpayment-20160728-gqfgwz.html|title=Delivery services Foodora and Deliveroo face claims of exploitation, underpayment|date=29 July 2016|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref> The Centre's \"Rights for Riders\" campaign aims \"to improve safety, pay, conditions and job security for food delivery riders\".<ref>Young Workers Centre, [http://www.youngworkers.org.au/rights4ridersfaq Rights for Riders FAQs], accessed 3 January 2017</ref>\n\nComplaints have also been made regarding the company's failure to provide cycle training and safety equipment (such as lights and [[Bicycle helmet|helmets]]) to its sometimes inexperienced riders. It has been argued that the need to race against the clock is another reason for risky cycling behaviour exhibited by the couriers; and that bikes should be checked for safety.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/deliveroo-cyclists-cause-road-mayhem-riding-against-the-clock-0m3l3rv0d|title=Deliveroo cyclists are accused of causing mayhem 'riding against the clock'|last2=Boswell|first2=Josh|date=5 June 2016|access-date=13 November 2016|first1=Grace|last1=Marsh|newspaper=The Sunday Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://road.cc/content/news/170695-deliveroo-criticised-letting-inexperienced-riders-loose-without-lights|title=Deliveroo criticised for letting inexperienced riders loose without lights|last=Laker|first=Laura|date=8 November 2016|website=road.cc|access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Strike ===\nDeliveroo's London drivers held a day-long strike in August 2016 to protest a new pay plan that they claimed would result in riders earning substantially below [[National Minimum Wage Act 1998|minimum wage]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/08/11/deliveroo-drivers-strike-in-row-over-pay-6060741/|title=Deliveroo drivers are on strike all day today in row over pay|first=Harry Readhead for|last=Metro.co.uk|date=11 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/aug/15/deliveroo-rider-after-an-accident-or-injury-we-are-on-our-own |title=Deliveroo rider: 'After an accident or injury we are on our own' - Business - The Guardian |date=15 August 2016 |accessdate=16 August 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815110950/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/aug/15/deliveroo-rider-after-an-accident-or-injury-we-are-on-our-own |archivedate=15 August 2016 }}</ref> and the continuing lack of sick and accident pay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/why-deliveroo-strike-matters-future-workers-rights-1575773|title=Why the Deliveroo strike matters for the future of workers' rights|date=12 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian1\"/> The company later abandoned these plans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/deliveroo-strike-contract-minimum-wage-protest-plans-wont-be-forced-a7195291.html|title=Deliveroo has scrapped plans to force its 'absurd' new contract on staff|date=17 August 2016|language=en-GB|access-date=19 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring these strikes, as a means of protest, London Deliveroo drivers held up signs containing the [[neologism]] \"Slaveroo\", a term formed as a contraction between \"slavery\" and the company's name. The term and its corresponding social media [[hashtag]] were adopted by several news outlets, including non-English international media.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=International Business Times|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/london-deliveroo-drivers-stage-protest-over-slaveroo-changes-pay-1575603|title=London Deliveroo drivers stage protest over 'slaveroo' changes in pay|date=11 August 2016|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://novaramedia.com/2016/10/27/slaveroo-industrial-action-and-cooperativism-what-does-the-future-of-the-digital-platform-economy-hold/|title=#Slaveroo, Industrial Action and Cooperativism: What Does the Future of the Digital Platform Economy Hold?|first=Jim|last=Benfield|date=27 October 2016|access-date=12 November 2016|publisher=[[Novara Media]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberation.fr/futurs/2016/08/12/a-londres-les-coursiers-de-deliveroo-deja-en-greve_1471994|newspaper=Lib\u00e9ration|title=A Londres, les coursiers de Deliveroo d\u00e9j\u00e0 en gr\u00e8ve|first=Perinne|last=Signoret|date=12 August 2016|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vn.nl/waarom-het-succes-van-de-deliveroo-staking-een-beetje-hoop-geeft/|publisher=Vrij Nederland|title=Waarom het succes van de Deliveroo-staking een beetje hoop geeft|first=Clara|last=van de Wiel|date=17 August 2016|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of these protests, chair of the Independent Workers Union of Great Britain Couriers and Logistics Branch, which represents couriers and delivery drivers in London, Mags Dewhurst, published an article in ''The Guardian'' backing the protesters, saying that Deliveroo's claim of freedom and flexibility vis-\u00e0-vis its couriers are sham, calling it \"exploitation and exhaustion\" instead.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/aug/16/deliveroo-couriers-strike-freedom-william-shu|title=Deliveroo couriers are right to strike: the company's claims of freedom are a sham|first=Mags|last=Dewhurst|date=16 August 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 November 2016, news headlines covered the demand of a small group of UK Deliveroo drivers to seek union recognition by the company. The Independent Workers Union of Great Britain (IWGB) represented the drivers in the [[Camden Town|Camden]] area of [[north London]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-britain-deliveroo-idUKKBN1331A7|title=After Uber case, UK union pushes for pay deal at Deliveroo|series=Technology News|date=8 November 2016|access-date=13 November 2016|publisher=REUTERS|first=Costas|last=Pitas|editor-first=Stephen|editor-last=Addison}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/deliveroo-union-minimum-wage-uber-workers-rights-ruling-a7404326.html|title=Deliveroo drivers demand union recognition and minimum wage after Uber workers' rights ruling|first=Ben|last=Chapman|date=8 November 2016|access-date=13 November 2016|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/32308032-a599-11e6-8898-79a99e2a4de6|title=Deliveroo couriers demand union recognition and rights in UK|series=Gig Economy|first=Madhumita|last=Murgia|date=8 November 2016|newspaper=The Financial Times|access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-37905425|title=Deliveroo riders seek to unionise and gain workers' rights|first=Clive|last=Coleman|newspaper=BBC News|date=8 November 2016|access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref> In November 2017, the Central Arbitration Committee dismissed the challenge by the IWGB and ruled that Deliveroo riders are self-employed. Deliveroo welcomed the decision as a 'victory for riders [who] value the flexibility that self-employment provides'.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/11/14/deliveroo-wins-landmark-legal-victory-riders-working-rights/|title=Deliveroo wins landmark legal victory against union claim|first=James|last=Titcomb|date=14 November 2017|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-November 2016, it was reported that Deliveroo's CEO, Will Shu, almost doubled his salary around the same time that low-paid Deliveroo drivers were demanding better employment conditions. Shu increased his pay to \u00a3102,135 in the year to December 2015, from \u00a353,333 the year before that.<ref name=\"Fury-as-Deliveroo-boss-nearly-doubles-his-pay-while-his-workers-fight\" />\n\nIn May 2017, Deliveroo workers protested working conditions in Berlin, Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.de/20170518/foodora-and-deliveroo-couriers-protest-working-conditions-in-berlin|title=Foodora and Deliveroo couriers protest working conditions in Berlin|date=18 May 2017|language=en-GB|access-date=1 March 2018}}</ref> In January 2018, Deliveroo riders went on strike in Belgium and in the Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/01/20/deliveroo-riders-go-strike-belgium-netherlands/|title=Deliveroo riders go on strike in Belgium and Netherlands|date=20 January 2018|language=en-GB|access-date=1 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===The Netherlands===\nIn 2017 and 2018 Dutch online consumer affairs journalist Tim Hofman investigated Deliveroo undercover, asserting that the company forced its delivery staff to declare themselves self-employed rather than being employees of the company, which would give them rights to benefits such as sick pay. The investigation and presentation of the evidence to Deliveroo management were released as episodes of the #BOOS online programme.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bogosavac |first1=Nina |title=Deliveroo nog meer onder druk na nieuwe undercover #Boos-aflevering |url=http://vance.nl/deliveroo-nog-meer-onder-druk-na-nieuwe-undercover-boos-aflevering/ |website=Vance |publisher=OKGO BV |accessdate=5 December 2019 |language=NL |date=23 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===London===\nIn London from 2019, it has been widely reported and confirmed that Deliveroo are paying its riders progressively less per delivery whilst pushing the pickup/delivery distances further for the lower fee.  It has been noted this practice in particular penalises scooter riders, who frequently find themselves being required to travel 1-2+ miles to perform a pickup, only to then undertake a delivery 3\u20134 miles away (totalling 5-6+), with no material visible distance benefit being paid over the base fee. The riders subsequently find themselves significantly 'out of zone', potentially in an area with low coverage, 'marooned', and no longer receiving orders unless they make the journey back in to zone first. This results in significant time wastage for the rider, undermining their ability to earn a reasonable hourly wage.\n\nAnother undermining tactic that has been observed is where riders, who might even have an excellent to exemplary 'performance statistic', arbitrarily have their previously reserved 'repeat' hours cut without warning, sometimes drastically (a cut of 4-plus days of work in a single week has been observed), from their pre-booking weekly calendar for no justifiable reason, thus seriously affecting the rider's ability to earn a stable income.  The reason given by Deliveroo was that the hours were given to other riders to meet the (over-subscribed) demand. This behaviour could potentially be interpreted as discriminatory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gigebyte.com/deliveroo-cuts-rider-fees-to-cover-longer-distances|title=Deliveroo cuts rider fees whilst at the same time covering longer distances|date=10 April 2019|language=en-GB|access-date=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*E McGaughey, 'Uber, the Taylor Review, and the duty to not misrepresent employment status' (2018) [https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3018516 Industrial Law Journal]\n*E McGaughey, 'Taylorooism: When Network Technology Meets Corporate Power' (2018) [https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3247605 Industrial Relations Journal]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Deliveroo}}\n*{{Official website|deliveroo.co.uk}}\n{{Online food ordering}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deliveroo}}\n[[Category:British companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Online companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Online food ordering]]\n[[Category:Companies based in the City of Westminster]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Ankman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory and basic operations:They pulled out of Germany as foot note 49 notes.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deliveroo"}
{"title_page": "Nangur Vishnu Temples", "text_new": "{{Infobox Hindu leader\n|name= [[Thirumangai Alvar]]\n|image= Thirumangai Alvar.jpg\n|caption = [[Thirumangai Alvar]] (left) with his wife Kumudavalli<br>(Thirunangur Tirupathis closely associated with the poet)\n|birth_date= \n|religion = [[Hinduism]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Vishnu temples at Nangur''' are a group of 11 temples near Nangur in [[Mayiladuthurai district]] of [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]. The eleven temples are part of the 108 [[Divya Desams]] of the Hindu god [[Vishnu]]. The temples at Nangur are believed to have been sanctified by [[Tirumangai Alvar]], one of the 12 ''[[Azhwar]]s''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=zVm1AAAAIAAJ \"Gazetteers of Tamil Nadu\"], p. 426, by B. S. Baliga</ref> The oldest of them have been dated to the reign of the Medieval [[Chola]] king [[Parantaka I]].\n\n==Festival==\nThe [[Thirumangai Alvar]] ''Mangalasasana utsavam'' (festival)<ref name=\"Garuda Sevai Festival\">{{cite news| \ntitle=Garuda Sevai|\nurl=http://www.ibiblio.org/sripedia/ramanuja/archives/feb08/pdfUQOxvBFB4v.pdf|format=PDF|\naccessdate= 2011-08-19}}</ref> in the month of Thai (Jan-Feb) on the New Moon day (Amavasai) witnesses [[11 Garuda sevai]] a spectacular event in which festival images idols from the 11 Thirunaangur ''[[Divyadesam]]'' shrines in the area are brought on [[Garuda]] mounts to Thirunangur. An idol of [[Thirumangai Alvar]] is also brought here on a ''Hamsa Vahanam'' (palanquin) and his ''paasurams'' (verses) dedicated to each of these 11 temples are recited. The ''[[Utsavar]]'' (festival deity) of [[Thirumangai Alvar]] and his consort Sri Kumudavalli Naachiyar are taken in a palanquin to each of the 11 temples, through the paddy fields in the area.  The ''paasurams'' (poems) dedicated to each of the 11 ''[[Divyadesam]]s'' are chanted in the respective shrines. This is the most important of the festivals in this area, and it draws thousands of visitors.\n\n==Thirunangur Tirupathis==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#FFC569\"\n! scope=\"col\" | '''Name of the temple'''\n! scope=\"col\" | '''Deity'''\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | '''Photo'''\n! scope=\"col\" | '''Notes/Beliefs'''\n|- align =\"center\"\n|-\n| [[Thirukkavalampadi]]\n| Gopalakrishna Perumal \n| [[File:Thirukavalambadi2.jpg|200x200px|center]]\n| ''Kavalam'' indicates garden and padi indicates place where cow and calf being taken for grassing - it is believed that [[Krishna]] given darshan to indra has Gopalan with cow. Once Lord krishna with his wife Bama helped Indra by killing naragasura and given back the Iravadam elephant kalpaka virsham etc.,taken by naragasura. Indra invited Krishna to his Deva loka. one day Bama(Krishna's Wife) asked Indrani (Indran's Wife) the parajatha flower worn by her, Indrani critisied Bama and refused to give her flower stating she is from Boo loka not qualified to wear the flower of devas. By seeing this lord Krishna forcibly taken the kalpaka virusha to his Dwaraka. Realising the disrespect committed by Indra to Krishna for not offering the flower he came to booloka and made one beautiful flower garden (kavalam) to worship Krishna, Pleased by Indras devotion lord Krisna given darshan as Gopalan with Cow and calf. From that time the place is called kavalampadi.\n|-\n| [[Thiruvanpurushothamam]]\n| Purushotama Perumal \n| [[File:Thrivuanpurushotam2.jpg|200px|center]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Thiruarimeya Vinnagaram]]\n| Kudamudakoothan Perumal\n|[[File:Arimeya Vinnagaram - Kuamadukoothan5.jpg|200px|center]]\n| ''Arimeya Vinnagaram'' literally translates to the place where Hari (another name of Vishnu) resides. It is believed that sage Uthanga performed his penance at this place. There is another local legend that Govardana (Vishnu) descended here at the request of [[Shiva]].\n|-\n| [[Thiruchsemponsey]]\n| Perarulaalan Perumal \n|[[File:Thiruchsemponsey2.jpg|200px|center]]\n| [[Rama]], the seventh avatar of Vishnu came to this place after killing Ravana. He made a golden idol of a cow and gifted to a [[Brahmin]] from the ashram of sage Dranethra, from where the place obtained its name.\n|-\n| [[Thirumanimadam]]\n|Badari Narayana Perumal \n|[[File:Narayana Perumal2.jpg|200x200px|center]]\n| The eleven [[Rudras]], called Ekadas Rudras and king of [[Deva (Hinduism)|devas]], [[Indra]], are believed to have worshiped Vishnu at this temple.<ref>{{cite book|title=South Indian Shrines: Illustrated|publisher=Asian Educational Services|page=242, 535|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NLSGFW1uZboC&pg=PA242&dq=govindaraja+perumal+temple&hl=en&sa=X&ei=221IUo_pJ4OG9QS9noGoAg&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=govindaraja%20perumal%20temple&f=false|last=Ayyar|first=P. V. Jagadisa|isbn=9788120601512|location=New Delhi|year=1982|ref=Ayyar}}</ref> The presiding deity of [[Badrinath Temple]], Badrinath, is believed to have visited the place on the request of [[Shiva]]. [[Ramanuja]] is believed to have learnt ''[[Tirumandiram]]'' from Thirukoshtiyur Nambi at this place.<ref name=\"R\">{{cite book|title=An introduction to religion and Philosophy - T\u00e9var\u00e1m and Tivviyappirapantam|url=https://archive.org/details/dli.jZY9lup2kZl6TuXGlZQdjZY2lZpy.TVA_BOK_0006115|last=R.|first=Dr. Vijayalakshmy|publisher=International Institute of Tamil Studies| location=Chennai|year=2001|edition=1st|ref=R.| page= 534-535}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Thiruvaikunda vinnagaram]]\n|Vaikunta Nathan Perumal \n|[[File:Vaikunda vinnagaram 2.jpg|200px|center]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Thiruthevanartthogai]]\n| Madhava Perumal Temple\n|[[File:Thiruthevanarthogai3.jpg|200px|center]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Thiruthetriyambalam]]\n| Palli Konda Perumal \n|[[File:Pallikonda Perumal - Thiruthetriambalam3.jpg|200px|center]]\n|It is believed that the presiding deity of [[Srirangam Ranganathaswamy temple]] arrived here on the request of [[Shiva]]. It is referred as ''Ambalam'', which in [[Malayalam]] means temple.\n|-\n| [[Thirumanikkoodam]]\n| Varadaraja Perumal\n|[[File:Thirumanikoodam2.jpg|200x200px|center]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Thiruvellakkulam]] or [[Annan Koil]]\n| Annan Perumal Temple\n|[[File:Annan koil.jpeg|200px|center]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Thiruppaarththanpalli]]\n|\n|[[File:Thiruparthanpalli4.jpg|200px|center]]\n|Krishna appeared to [[Arjuna]], a [[Pandava]] prince as Parthasarathy and initiated his knowledge to understand who he actually was. Since Parthasarathy initiated education here for Arjuna, the place is called Parthanpalli. (''Parthan'' + ''Palli'', meaning school\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Thirunangur Tirupathis}}\n{{Famous Vishnu temples}}\n{{Mayiladuthurai Topics}}\n[[Category:Divya Desams| ]]\n[[Category:Vishnu temples in Mayiladuthurai district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Hindu leader\n|name= [[Thirumangai Alvar]]\n|image= Thirumangai Alvar.jpg\n|caption = [[Thirumangai Alvar]] (left) with his wife Kumudavalli<br>(Thirunangur Tirupathis closely associated with the poet)\n|birth_date= \n|religion = [[Hinduism]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Vishnu temples at Nangur''' are a group of 11 temples near Nangur in [[Mayiladuthurai district]] of [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]. The eleven temples are part of the 108 [[Divya Desams]] of the Hindu god [[Vishnu]]. The temples at Nangur are believed to have been sanctified by [[Tirumangai Alvar]], one of the 12 ''[[Azhwar]]s''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=zVm1AAAAIAAJ \"Gazetteers of Tamil Nadu\"], p. 426, by B. S. Baliga</ref> The oldest of them have been dated to the reign of the Medieval [[Chola]] king [[Parantaka I]].\n\n==Festival==\nThe [[Thirumangai Alvar]] ''Mangalasasana utsavam'' (festival)<ref name=\"Garuda Sevai Festival\">{{cite news| \ntitle=Garuda Sevai|\nurl=http://www.ibiblio.org/sripedia/ramanuja/archives/feb08/pdfUQOxvBFB4v.pdf|format=PDF|\naccessdate= 2011-08-19}}</ref> in the month of Thai (Jan-Feb) on the New Moon day (Amavasai) witnesses [[11 Garuda sevai]] a spectacular event in which festival images idols from the 11 Thirunaangur ''[[Divyadesam]]'' shrines in the area are brought on [[Garuda]] mounts to Thirunangur. An idol of [[Thirumangai Alvar]] is also brought here on a ''Hamsa Vahanam'' (palanquin) and his ''paasurams'' (verses) dedicated to each of these 11 temples are recited. The ''[[Utsavar]]'' (festival deity) of [[Thirumangai Alvar]] and his consort Sri Kumudavalli Naachiyar are taken in a palanquin to each of the 11 temples, through the paddy fields in the area.  The ''paasurams'' (poems) dedicated to each of the 11 ''[[Divyadesam]]s'' are chanted in the respective shrines. This is the most important of the festivals in this area, and it draws thousands of visitors.\n\n==Thirunangur Tirupathis==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#FFC569\"\n! scope=\"col\" | '''Name of the temple'''\n! scope=\"col\" | '''Deity'''\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | '''Photo'''\n! scope=\"col\" | '''Notes/Beliefs'''\n|- align =\"center\"\n|-\n| [[Thirukkavalampadi]]\n| Gopalakrishna Perumal \n| [[File:Thirukavalambadi2.jpg|200x200px|center]]\n| ''Kavalam'' indicates garden and padi indicates place where cow and calf being taken for grassing - it is believed that [[Krishna]] given darshan to indra has Gopalan with cow. Once Lord krishna with his wife Bama helped Indra by killing naragasura and given back the Iravadam elephant kalpaka virsham etc.,taken by naragasura. Indra invited Krishna to his Deva loka. one day Bama(Krishna's Wife) asked Indrani (Indran's Wife) the parajatha flower worn by her, Indrani critisied Bama and refused to give her flower stating she is from Boo loka not qualified to wear the flower of devas. By seeing this lord Krishna forcibly taken the kalpaka virusha to his Dwaraka. Realising the disrespect committed by Indra to Krishna for not offering the flower he came to booloka and made one beautiful flower garden (kavalam) to worship Krishna, Pleased by Indras devotion lord Krisna given darshan as Gopalan with Cow and calf. From that time the place is called kavalampadi.\n|-\n| [[Thiruvanpurushothamam]]\n| Purushotama Perumal \n| [[File:Thrivuanpurushotam2.jpg|200px|center]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Thiruarimeya Vinnagaram]]\n| Kudamudakoothan Perumal\n|[[File:Arimeya Vinnagaram - Kuamadukoothan5.jpg|200px|center]]\n| ''Arimeya Vinnagaram'' literally translates to the place where Hari (another name of Vishnu) resides. It is believed that sage Uthanga performed his penance at this place. There is another local legend that Govardana (Vishnu) descended here at the request of [[Shiva]].\n|-\n| [[Thiruchsemponsey]]\n| Perarulaalan Perumal \n|[[File:Thiruchsemponsey2.jpg|200px|center]]\n| [[Rama]], the seventh avatar of Vishnu came to this place after killing Ravana. He made a golden idol of a cow and gifted to a [[Brahmin]] from the ashram of sage Dranethra, from where the place obtained its name.\n|-\n| [[Thirumanimadam]]\n|Badari Narayana Perumal \n|[[File:Narayana Perumal2.jpg|200x200px|center]]\n| The eleven [[Rudras]], called Ekadas Rudras and king of [[Deva (Hinduism)|devas]], [[Indra]], are believed to have worshiped Vishnu at this temple.<ref>{{cite book|title=South Indian Shrines: Illustrated|publisher=Asian Educational Services|page=242, 535|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NLSGFW1uZboC&pg=PA242&dq=govindaraja+perumal+temple&hl=en&sa=X&ei=221IUo_pJ4OG9QS9noGoAg&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=govindaraja%20perumal%20temple&f=false|last=Ayyar|first=P. V. Jagadisa|isbn=9788120601512|location=New Delhi|year=1982|ref=Ayyar}}</ref> The presiding deity of [[Badrinath Temple]], Badrinath, is believed to have visited the place on the request of [[Shiva]]. [[Ramanuja]] is believed to have learnt ''[[Tirumandiram]]'' from Thirukoshtiyur Nambi at this place.<ref name=\"R\">{{cite book|title=An introduction to religion and Philosophy - T\u00e9var\u00e1m and Tivviyappirapantam|url=https://archive.org/details/dli.jZY9lup2kZl6TuXGlZQdjZY2lZpy.TVA_BOK_0006115|last=R.|first=Dr. Vijayalakshmy|publisher=International Institute of Tamil Studies| location=Chennai|year=2001|edition=1st|ref=R.| page= 534-535}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Thiruvaikunda vinnagaram]]\n|Vaikunta Nathan Perumal \n|[[File:Vaikunda vinnagaram 2.jpg|200px|center]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Thiruthevanartthogai]]\n| Madhava Perumal Temple\n|[[File:Thiruthevanarthogai3.jpg|200px|center]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Thiruthetriyambalam]]\n| Palli Konda Perumal \n|[[File:Pallikonda Perumal - Thiruthetriambalam3.jpg|200px|center]]\n|It is believed that the presiding deity of [[Srirangam Ranganathaswamy temple]] arrived here on the request of [[Shiva]]. It is referred as ''Ambalam'', which in [[Malayalam]] means temple.\n|-\n| [[Thirumanikkoodam]]\n| Varadaraja Perumal\n|[[File:Thirumanikoodam2.jpg|200x200px|center]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Thiruvellakkulam]] or [[Annan Koil]]\n| Annan Perumal Temple\n|[[File:Annan koil.jpeg|200px|center]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Thiruppaarththanpalli]]\n|\n|[[File:Thiruparthanpalli4.jpg|200px|center]]\n|Krishna appeared to [[Arjuna]], a [[Pandava]] prince as Parthasarathy and initiated his knowledge to understand who he actually was. Since Parthasarathy initiated education here for Arjuna, the place is called Parthanpalli. (''Parthan'' + ''Palli'', meaning school\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Thirunangur Tirupathis}}\n{{Famous Vishnu temples}}\n{{Mayiladuthurai Topics}}\n[[Category:Divya Desams| ]]\n[[Category:Vishnu temples in Mayiladuthurai district]]\n[[Category:Villages in Mayiladuthurai district]]\n\n{{Mayiladuthurai-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kesev Baskaran", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nangur_Vishnu_Temples"}
